<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT, August 21 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR -- Visiting Chinese Premier Li Peng today
expressed his confidence that the friendly relations and
cooperation between China and Malaysia will experience new and
greater development.
</P>
<P>
"Our two peoples have enjoyed a long history of friendship with
each other and have steadily expanded cooperation in various
fields," Li said at a grand banquet tonight hosted in his honor by
his Malaysian counterpart Mahathir Mohammed.
</P>
<P>
Li, who arrived here earlier today for a four-day friendly
official visit to Malaysia, believed his official talks with
Mahathir tomorrow will be of "great importance to continuous
development of our bilateral relations".
</P>
<P>
BELGRADE -- The Bosnian Serb government issued a statement here
Wednesday accusing the Multinational Stablization Force (SFOR)
and the International Police Task Force (IPTF) for their forcible
occupation of the police headquarters in Banja Luka.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, the SFOR and IPTF occupied with force the
building of the police headquarters and the three police stations
in the city of Banja Luka. They did so in the name of the Interior
Ministry of the Serb Republic, the Yugoslavia Tanjug news agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
Three-hundred-and-fifty British and Czech soldiers, 50 armored
vehicles and several helicopters participated in the action.
</P>
<P>
The action took place following Bosnian Serb President Biljana
Plavsic's meeting with the International High Representative to
Bosnia, Carlos Westendorp, and the United States envoy, Robert
Gelbard.
</P>
<P>
BONN -- German Chancellor Helmut Kohl today said he was aware
of Finance Minister Theo Waigel's plan to quit after the general
elections in September next year.
</P>
<P>
"I respect his position and understand his decision, especially
since I know he is not tired of serving in office," Kohl said in a
statement released in Bonn.
</P>
<P>
In a radio interview on Tuesday evening, Waigel stunned
political observers by saying he would leave his office should
Kohl's center-right coalition win next year's elections.
</P>
<P>
Waigel, who has served as finance minister in Kohl's
center-right government since April 1989, said he was not tired of
holding the office. 
</P>
</TEXT>
