<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mugabe, Former Fighters Hold Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert
Mugabe today began meeting the national leadership of former
freedom fighters who for the past weeks have been pressing
government for liberation war compensation payments.
</P>
<P>
The meeting at Mugabe's official residence, Zimbabwe House,
comes after hundreds of ex-combatants resorted to picketing
ruling ZANU (PF) party and government offices, including the
presidential residence, demanding disbursement of disability
pensions.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe, patron of the Zimbabwe Liberation War Veterans
Association, agreed to meet and hear grievances of ex-combatants
following weeks of unrest among the ranks of former freedom
fighters, which recently saw the looting of the ruling ZANU (PF)
headquarters in Harare and the disruption of commemorations
marking Heroes Day on August 11.
</P>
<P>
Former combatants have been demonstrating since April
following the suspension of war victims compensation payments
after many undeserving people, including ministers and senior
government officials, were found to have been beneficiaries of
the war victims compensation fund, with about 450 million
Zimbabwe Dollars (about 45 million u.s. dollars) parcelled out in
just eight months.
</P>
<P>
In his introductory remarks, Mugabe said he had noted that the
war veterans disapproved of the presence of some high ranking
members of ZANU (PF) and government, but assured ex-combatants
that they did not have enemies either within the ruling party or
in his cabinet.
</P>
<P>
''We may differ in expression of ideas but no one can lift his
hand and say I am opposed to ex-combatants, otherwise he would
not be in my government,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe said he had gone through the eight-point document from
the War Veterans Association and in principle agreed with its
contents.
</P>
<P>
''I have seen your list of grievances and recommendations and
they are in agreement in principle with what is coming from the
government and party. Maybe they might differ in substance,''
said Mugabe.
</P>
<P>
After the introductory remarks, the meeting was closed to the
press. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
