<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inflation in July Drops in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's year-on-year
inflation dropped 2.3 percentage points to just more than 19
percent in July, surprising most market analysts who expected the
figure to be much higher following a spate of administered price
increases in recent months.
</P>
<P>
The inflation figure declined to 19.1 percent, down from 21.4
percent in June, as analysts warned of severe inflationary
pressures.
</P>
<P>
The downward trend was again mainly due to falling food prices
which saw prices for fruits and vegetables declining by 17.8
percent between June and July.
</P>
<P>
The overall food basket, which has the largest weighting in
the computation of the consumer price index (cpi), dropped 4.2
percent over the same period.
</P>
<P>
However, analysts today warned that inflation could rise
slightly in August as a result of the knock-on effect of recent
wage and salary settlement which averaged 25 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970822.0008 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> High Street Boom in Britain Renews Rate Fears </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 21 (Xinhua) -- High street sales in Britain are
growing faster than at any time since the economic boom of the
late 1980s, according to the Office for National Statistics (ONS).
</P>
<P>
Retail sales in July were 6.5 percent up on a year earlier and
higher than expectations in the City of around 5.9 percent. One
City economist said this was the fastest growth rate anywhere in
the world except Slovakia.
</P>
<P>
In the three months from May to July retail sales rose 2.1
percent on the previous quarter, the highest rise since October
1987's 2.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Government economists regard the quarterly figures as a more
reliable indicator of consumer trends. Geoffrey Robinson,
paymaster general, thought the growth rate was "entirely expected"
as consumers spent windfalls from building society flotations.
</P>
<P>
"If there were to be a sustained boom over a long period...
then of course we would review the situation," he said.
</P>
<P>
The ONS said that it wanted to wait until the August figures
before deciding whether the growth inspired by spending of
windfall gains from building society and insurance mutual
flotations had begun to slow down.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of England, meanwhile, published figures showing that
the broad money supply measure M4 -- cash plus bank and building
society accounts -- rose by 11.8 percent in the year to July, the
highest since 1990.
</P>
<P>
The Bank warned in its Inflation Report last week that the
current rate of M4 growth "may not be compatible with the
inflation target in the medium term". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
