<HEADLINE> S. Leone Junta, Militia Renew Fighting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Heavy fighting broke out today
between the government army and local militiamen known as
Kamajors in southern Sierra Leone, killing one woman and a
soldier.
</P>
<P>
A report reaching here said the fighting erupted early this
morning at a town 22 miles from bo, the second largest city of
the country, as the kamajors tried to capture the military
garrison in the area.
</P>
<P>
During the five-hour battle, with heavy artillery used by both
sides, the Kamajors were repelled while the military reportedly
captured a number of weapons, including bombs and ak47 automatic
rifles, from the fleeing Kamajors.
</P>
<P>
A source was quoted as saying that the Kamajors, who are well
armed, are backed by the former militia fighters of the defunct
ULIMO-K from neighboring Liberia.
</P>
<P>
This is the second time that military garrisons have been
attacked since the country's coup on May 25 that toppled the
civilian government led by ousted President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
