<DOCNO> XIE19970822.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Launches Consultation Paper on New Transport Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 21 (Xinhua) -- British Deputy Prime Minister
John Prescott Thursday unveiled the government's first thoughts on
an integrated and more environmentally friendly transport
strategy.
</P>
<P>
Serving as a discussion document in advance of a White Paper
next Spring, the document poses 27 questions to be answered during
the public consultation period.
</P>
<P>
One of the questions is whether there is "a role for making
greater use of economic instruments to influence how people choose
to travel", which include increasing the price of public parking,
taxing company car parks and charging for the use of roads.
</P>
<P>
Although the document accepts that the car remains an "integral
part of modern society", it believes that a "better balance" is
needed between cars and public transport.
</P>
<P>
Prescott told a news conference that by improving public
transport and giving it priority over the private car, people
could be drawn into using buses and trains.
</P>
<P>
He also pointed out that he wanted to reverse the trend towards
UK families having two cars, saying "two cars is a symptom of the
failure of the public transport system rather than prosperity".
</P>
<P>
Several concrete suggestions for improving public transport
were made by the consultation paper, which include a new
regulatory framework for Britain's privatized railway system.
</P>
<P>
It is forecast that there will be a rise of between 36 and 57
percent in road traffic levels in Britain over the next 20 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
