<HEADLINE> S. Africans Trade Union Demands Better Work </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 21 (Xinhua) -- About 12,000 people
marched to the offices of business South Africa here today to
present a memorandum, urging the capitalist side to revise its
positions on clauses of the basic conditions of employment bill.
</P>
<P>
The demonstrators, all members of Congress of South Africa
Trade Union (COSATU), demanded six months' maternity leave, 16 as
the minimum age for employment, and a 40-hour week, phased in
over five years.
</P>
<P>
It was against children to work under the age of 16 because
they should be at school, COSATU sources said.
</P>
<P>
Also today, thousands of COSATU members held demonstrations in
Pretoria, the administrative capital of the country, to hand over
a memorandum to the labor department, outlining their grievances.
</P>
<P>
Similar actions were organized in other provinces earlier in
the week, informed sources said, noting a 24-hour national strike
would take place soon.
</P>
<P>
Traffic was severely disrupted by the demonstrations. Some
motorists were stuck in traffic for up to an hour, while
municipal buses were also delayed and diverted along alternative
routes, traffic department officials said.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of policemen, some in riot gear, kept watch and
dozens of traffic officials were deployed to cope with
disruptions, they said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
