<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PNA Implements Boycott of Israeli Goods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) today began enforcing a boycott of Israeli goods
in protest against Israel's economic sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian police in the West Bank city of Nablus prevented
several trucks from bringing Israeli-made goods into the
city. And in another West Bank city of Tulkarm, shoppers were
ordered by the PNA not to purchase Israeli goods that were
black-listed.
</P>
<P>
The nine-member PNA Cabinet approved last Saturday a gradual
boycott of Israeli goods as a major step to counter the continued
Israeli closure and freeze of most of the tax revenues.
</P>
<P>
In the wake of the July 30 twin suicide bombings in
Jerusalem's Mahane Yehuda market which killed 16 people, Israel
immediately imposed a total closure on Palestinian territories,
barred tens of thousands of Palestinian workers from working in
Israel, and suspended the transferring of tax revenues to the PNA
as part of pressure put on the PNA to crack down on terrorism.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions have inflicted severe hardships on the
Palestinian people and were condemned by the PNA as "declaration
of war." In a gesture to reward the PNA's partially resumed
security cooperation, the Israeli government transferred on
Tuesday 4.2 million U.S. dollars of the total withheld 14 million
dollars tax money to the PNA.
</P>
<P>
The PNA embargo list complied by the cabinet ranged from
cigarettes to TV sets, items that can be replaced with
Palestinian goods or imported from elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
However, it is believed that the Palestinian boycott was more
a political statement than an actual threat to Israel, since
Israel can prevent the PNA from importing goods from other
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970822.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Heavy Air Pollution, Plus Hot Weather, Haunts Paris </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The French capital Paris today
pulled its degree two alarm of heavy air pollution on the second
consecutive day, with all its districts and suburbs registering
level two pollution, or more than 180 micrograms of ozone per
cubic meter.
</P>
<P>
Agence France-Presse said that Paris is living under its worst
pollution since the alarming episode of pollution began in the
first week of this month.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the concentration of another polluting chemical
element, nitrogen dioxide (NO2), which can partly turn into ozone
in summertime, has also reached level two in Paris, with 300
micrograms of NO2 per cubic meter registered at the barometer of
the official air supervising instrument Airparif.
</P>
<P>
Paris has been living under heavy sunshine weather for weeks.
The dry and hot weather, which has contributed to the rise of
ozone and NO2 pollutions, is expected to continue for days.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
