<HEADLINE> 800 Hostages Freed from Chechen Captivity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Almost 800 hostages and prisoners
of war, including 11 Russian reporters, were released from Chechen
captivity over the past 12 months, Secretary of the Russian
Security Council Ivan Rybkin said today.
</P>
<P>
The Itar-Tass quoted Rybkin as reporting that Chechen bandits
captured over 70 people since May 1 alone. Out of the total, 40
captives were released.
</P>
<P>
Calling the capture of hostages in Chechnya "a dirty business",
Rybkin said two deputy secretaries at the Security Council staff
constantly work on this problem.
</P>
<P>
According to another report, Rybkin told journalists Wednesday
that about 1400 people are missing or being held hostage in
Chechnya, including many foreigners.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Russian leadership is concerned about the problem
of hostages and "Chechnya should understand this."
</P>
<P>
Rybkin believes that "both presidents (Boris Yeltsin of Russia
and Aslan Maskhadov of Chechnya) are interested in finding out
the substance of this process. And the result should be the truth,
not a new lie." 
</P>
</TEXT>
