<HEADLINE> Nigerian Troops Block Major Road in S. Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian troops based in Jul,
13 miles east of the Sierra Leone capital here, have blocked the
main highway leading to the interior of the country, Sierra Leone
military officials charged today.
</P>
<P>
"They are turning back vehicles and people saying they should
not go through and if they argue they would be shot," a military
spokesman told Xinhua here.
</P>
<P>
He said that there have been "a series of skirmishes between
the Sierra Leone army and Nigerian soldiers in the area during
the past two days."
</P>
<P>
"It seemed as if they are up to some war games but we are also
on the alert," he said.
</P>
<P>
A people's army spokesman, commenting on the developments,
said, "Nigerian troops have been pushing their luck, They have no
business here. This is our land and they should stop molesting
our people and erecting checkpoints on our soil."
</P>
<P>
A Nigerian military officer reached by telephone by Xinhua at
the Jul base confirmed the act, saying, "We have now taken the
decision to close the road temporarily to safeguard our security.
We have come under snipers shots too frequently."
</P>
<P>
Over 200 commuters, mostly traders, are mow allegedly stranded
on both sides of the barrier.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian troops have been sent there as among the west African
peace-keeping force (ECOMOG) which frowns on the May 25 coup that
toppled the civilian government in Sierra Leone. For this, the
Nigerians have accused soldier of the military junta of attacking
their positions in the country.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the third high-ranking member of the rebel
movement, Lt. Colonel Eddie Collins is to be sworn in as Minister
of Trade and State Enterprises tomorrow, official sources Said.
</P>
<P>
The post has been vacant. The movement has three ministerial
posts in the military government of Major Jommy Paul Koroma.
</P>
</TEXT>
