<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-21 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Welcomes Security Council Position on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The Cypriot government has
welcomed U.N. Security Council's position that the Turkish Cypriot
side is blamed for the stalemate in efforts for a settlement to
the Cyprus problem, a government spokesman said today.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council was concerned and disappointed over the
fact that the Turkish Cypriot side tried to block any substantive
progress and introduce terms which are contrary to the council's
resolutions and also rejected by the European Union (EU),
spokesman Manolis Christofides told his daily briefing.
</P>
<P>
After a Security Council briefing Wednesday by the
Secretary-General's Special Advisor for Cyprus Diego Cordovez who
chaired the two rounds of direct talks between the Greek Cypriot
and Turkish Cypriot sides, its President John Weston told the
press that "there was a sense of disappointment" that progress was
not reached during the talks.
</P>
<P>
"There was a sense that commendation was due to (Cypriot)
President (Glafcos) Clerides for the flexibility and cooperation
that he had shown at this round of talks," Weston said.
</P>
<P>
He added there was also "some concern and disappointment that
further substantive progress at this time was impeded by
the attempt to bring preconditions to the table by the other
party, and here of course I mean the Turkish Cypriots."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman welcomed the reference made to Clerides' stance
during the talks held last week in Glion, Switzerland and said the
Cypriot government remains committed to the procedure for a
solution to the Cyprus problem through the U.N. peace efforts.
</P>
<P>
"We are ready to cooperate fully in this direction," he
added.
</P>
<P>
However, Christofides said that "it is up to the U.N. to find
ways to handle this temporary impasse the Turkish side's
intransigence has created" and decide on the procedure it will
follow to solve the Cyprus problem and implement its resolutions
on Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
The Glion talks ended in deadlock last Friday because the
Turkish Cypriot side insisted the EU postpone or reverse its
decision to begin accession talks with Cyprus next year.
</P>
<P>
The first round of U.N.-sponsored talks between Clerides and
Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash was held in Troutbeck, near
New York, in July.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman called on the international community to exert
pressure on Ankara which he described as "the key" to the solution
to the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus problem has remained unresolved since 1974 when the
island was divided after the Turkish troops invaded and took over
the northern third of it in the wake of a failed coup seeking with
Greece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
