<HEADLINE> Fighting Renews in Somali </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Fighting has again renewed
between the forces of Hussein Aidid and the Rahanwein Resistance
Army (RRA) fighters in Dhiil village, 32 km north of the Bakol
regional capital, Huddor.
</P>
<P>
According to reports from the area, fighting occurred
Wednesday afternoon when the loyalists of Hussein Aidid launched
an attack on Dhiil in an attempt to regain control of the
village.
</P>
<P>
Both factions claimed to have gained the upper hand in the
fighting and the control of the village.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for Hussein Aidid's side said their men have
over-run those of the RRA and regained five technical battle
vehicles they lost last Friday to the RRA.
</P>
<P>
Hussein Aidid's men also admitted to have lost five of their
fighters after inflicting heavy losses on the Rahanwein gunmen.
</P>
<P>
On the RRA side, Mr. Mohamud Ali Aden Qalinle also claimed to
have won in the fighting over Hussein Aidid's men, saying they
fought back after being provoked by Aidid's supporters.
</P>
<P>
As RRA spokesman, Qalinle further claimed they had killed 17
of Hussein Aidid's fighters and lost only four of his men and
suffered other six wounded.
</P>
<P>
Qalinle also said they destroyed four of 26 technical vehicles
used by Hussein Aidid in the clashes before they fled the area.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, there is no independent confirmation regarding
the rival claims, but sources from Huddor town said two burned
technical vehicles and another non-functioning battle wagon were
seen being dragged along by Aidis's vehicles toward the capital
Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
He warned the Somali businessmen against using the roads in
Bay and Bakol regions.
</P>
<P>
The warning came after a land mine blew up a civilian truck
mounted with a towing machine, with the driver and another man
killed near Awdinle village last week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
