<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African Countries Keen on Joining SADC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 21 (Xinhua) -- A number of African
countries, including the Democratic Republic of Congo and
Madagascar, have signaled their intention to join the Southern
African Development Community (SADC), informed sources said
today.
</P>
<P>
The honorary consul's office of Madagascar and the Congo (K)
embassy had confirmed their interest Wednesday, with the former
saying that moves were under way to make a formal application,
the sources said.
</P>
<P>
A Madagascar official was quoted as saying that her
government's membership of the Common Market for Eastern and
Southern African (COMESA) treaty would hang in the balance.
</P>
<P>
Congo (K) is also a member of COMESA and has been involved in
the SADC's sectoral cooperation projects.
</P>
<P>
Regional sources said Seychelles had also expressed interest
in SADC.
</P>
<P>
A draft agenda of the forthcoming SADC summit shows the
meeting will discuss membership applications from unnamed states.
</P>
<P>
The SADC, which has been seeking to create a free trade area
since it was set up in August 1992, admitted Mauritius as its
12th member one year ago.
</P>
<P>
For now, the SADC consists of Angola, Botswana, Zimbabwe,
Lesotho, Malawi, Mozambique, Namibia, Swaziland, Tanzania,
Zambia, South Africa and Mauritius.
</P>
<P>
Observers believe that the SADC's attractiveness comes from
its new program of action, including a free trade zone of about
140 million people.
</P>
<P>
Others say that the inclusion of South Africa has improved the
region's standing among potential foreign investors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
