<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Oil Companies Criticized for Price </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government today
criticized three local oil companies for price increases
following the depreciation of the Kenyan Shilling against the
U.S. Dollar.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued here today, Crispus Mutitu, Permanent
Secretary of the Energy Ministry, termed the price increases by
Mobil, Kenya Shell and BP as "unrealistic and inflammatory".
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that oil companies had increased pump prices in
the past week with Mobil raising oil price by 3.02 Shillings per
liter, Kenya Shell 2.04 Shillings and BP 2.04 Shillings.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan official noted that the price increase should not
exceed about 1.45 Shillings per liter in accordance with the
assessment by his ministry on the basis of the latest Murban spot
prices and the current average Shilling exchange rate.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that oil companies were always expected to
increase prices to aggravate the suffering of the average Kenyans
when the country's economy was undergoing some difficulties.
</P>
<P>
The seven multi-national oil companies operating in the east
African country have formed cartels with monopolistic tendencies
including charging unreasonable prices and driving smaller firms
out of the market.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan government has threatened to fix maximum prices for
petroleum products in line with the international market as a
measure to protect consumers from exploitation.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that 13 private oil firms had been licensed to
operate in the country in a bid to encourage competition against
multi-national oil companies.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan government is also considering to take legal
measures for better management of the deregulated petroleum
market which should have benefited consumers.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the state-owned National Oil Corporation of Kenya
and the Kenya Pipeline Company are scheduled to invest in service
stations, liquified petroleum gas import terminals and other
facilities to provide alternative and more flexible supply points
for petroleum products. 
</P>
</TEXT>
