<HEADLINE> Texas Train Collision Kill Two Crew Members </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 21 (Xinhua) -- A runaway Union Pacific train
with no one aboard collided head-on with another train in Forth
Worth in Texas of The United States, killing two crew members and
setting off a large fire. It was the railroad's second fatal
collision in two months.
</P>
<P>
The crash shortly before midnight Wednesday also injured
another crew member, while another escaped unharmed, news reports
said.
</P>
<P>
A large fire erupted after the accident as more than 8,000
gallons of diesel fuel leaked from the engines and ignited. About
60 firefighters brought the blaze under control by early morning.
</P>
<P>
A Union Pacific spokesman said Thursday that an unmanned train,
somehow rolled from a siding onto the track being used by a
westbound freight which had five locomotives and 114 cars.
</P>
<P>
The unmanned train had rolled nearly 10 miles when it collided
with the freight train in west Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
The victims were identified as engineers.
</P>
<P>
On June 22, four people were killed and one was severely burned
when two Union Pacific freight trains collided head-on on a single
stretch of track in Devine, about 30 miles southwest of San
Antonio.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, Union Pacific announced that it was
spending millions of dollars over the next three years to upgrade
its computer-aided dispatching system to make tracks safer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
