<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Expects Good Economic Growth, Budget Balance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 21 (Xinhua) -- French Minister of Finance and
Economy Dominique Strauss-Kahn said today that France's gross
domestic product (GDP) growth rate should attain 2.8-2.9 percent
in 1998, while its inflation could be controlled under 1.5
percent.
</P>
<P>
However, he said he based the figure only on the expected
performances by public enterprises, whose production growth rates
are usually lower than private enterprises.
</P>
<P>
French officials said that the government will strictly control
its spending rise in 1998 to about 1.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
Agence France-Presse quoted authorized sources as saying that
the public deficit will be "very close to" 3 percent of the GDP
in the 1998 budget law, in conformity with the European Union's
budgetary criteria for joining the euro, the European single
currency.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that the new budget law will require the
government to reduce its 1998 spending by an equivalent of 0.5
percent of the GDP through belt-tightening measures, as is
compared with its spending in 1997.
</P>
<P>
This year's public deficit of France is expected to stand at
3.5 percent of the GDP, according to an earlier estimation made in
April.
</P>
<P>
The figures are very close to the project made by the former
government of Prime Minister Alain Juppe, which predicted a 2.8
percent growth of GDP in 1998, after a 2.3 percent growth in 1997.
</P>
<P>
While the French franc dropped by 20 percent in its exchange
rate with the U.S. dollar so far this year, inflation rate stayed
at an average of 1 percent in France over the past 12 months.
</P>
<P>
The French central bank, la Banque de France, today decided to
maintain its key interests rates unchanged at its first session of
board of monetary policy, after the German Bundesbank decided to
maintain its interest rates earlier this week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
