<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 21 (Xinhua) -- FBI agents have read through
Terry Nichols' prison mail, seeking clues or information about
other possible suspects in the Oklahoma City bombing in 1995, an
FBI agent testified in Denver, Colorado, Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"What I was looking for was information that possibly could
indicate another person that may be involved in this incident,"
agent Mark White was quoted as saying by the Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
He said he and nearly two dozen other FBI agents also sought
any information that may have been significant about the bombing.
</P>
<P>
White was the first FBI agent to testify at a hearing today in
which U.S. District Judge Richard Matsch is trying to find out
what authorities may have learned by inspecting the prison mail of
both Nichols and co-defendant Timothy McVeigh, who was sentenced
to death earlier.
</P>
<P>
Nichols is scheduled to stand trial on September 29 on murder,
conspiracy and weapons-related counts in the April 19, 1995,
bombing of the Alfred P. Murrah Federal Building in Oklahoma, that
killed 168 people and injured more than 500 others. If convicted,
he faces the death penalty. 
