<HEADLINE> Zambia to Ban Trading Near New Lusaka City Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government announced
here today that it will prosecute any vendors trading within a
radius of 200 metres away from the newly opened Lusaka city
market with effect from September first.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Local Government and Housing Bennie Mwiinga said
that Cairo Road and Lumumba Road, business centers of the capital
city, are also out of bounds for the vendors.
</P>
<P>
He said the move has been taken to persuade people to trade in
the city market which has all the facilities to ensure food is
hygienically stored.
</P>
<P>
He warned that the vendors who leave the city market to trade
outside and those who have been given stalls in the market but do
not take them up by next Tuesday risk having their stalls
forfeited and re-allocated accordingly.
</P>
<P>
Mwiinga said the government has spent huge sums of money to
build the market and it will be unfortunate to see the market
turn into a white elephant by allowing street vendors to trade in
the corridors of the market with 3,000 stalls.
</P>
<P>
The vendors are accused of blocking customers from entering
the biggest market in the capital.
</P>
<P>
Some marketeers have abandoned their new stands inside the
market to come and trade outside, where there is more business.
</P>
<P>
Numerous street vendors do the business in Lusaka's downtown
centers because of inadequate market places. The city market was
opened earlier this month as part of the government's efforts to
solve the problem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
