<DOCNO> XIE19970822.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Crisis Avoidable: IMF Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The financial crisis that
shook Thailand is avoidable and could have been eased had the
government imposed strict financial controls sooner, the
International Monetary Fund chief stated here today.
</P>
<P>
However, Michael Camdessus, the IMF's Managing Director told a
press conference that Thai authorities belatedly moved "very
boldly" to restore economic stability, including imposing higher
taxes and closing 58 financial institutions, which is two thirds
of the country's total that made bad loans to property developers.
</P>
<P>
The press conference was held following the IMF approved the
first part of a 16.7 billion dollar rescue package for Thailand on
Wednesday, which is some 3.9 billion dollars equivalent.
</P>
<P>
The IMF said 1.6 billion dollars will go to Thailand right away
and an additional 810 million dollars after November 30, provided
Thailand meets IMF conditions. Subsequent disbursements will be
made quarterly.
</P>
<P>
Camdessus said the rapid approval should reassure global
financial markets that the safety net set up after the Mexican
peso crisis in 1995 works. The Thai bailout was the world's second
largest after the IMF and the United States came up with 50
billion dollars for Mexico two years ago.
</P>
<P>
"I am confident that the comprehensive policy measures adopted
by the Thai authorities, supported by the additional financing
package that has been put together by countries of the region and
other multilateral institutions-- the total amount available is
over 16 billion U.S. dollars -- will restore stability and set the
stage for an effective recovery of the Thai economy," Camdessus
said.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that starting in early 1996 everything was done
to give the Thai authorities advice and warning of the looming
problems but only short of an "undiplomatic public outburst" to
make Thais aware of the risks.
</P>
<P>
Camdessus said the worst of the Thai crisis will be over if
Bangkok follows through with its austerity measures, including
cutting its defense budget.
</P>
<P>
He stressed Thailand's problems "could have been corrected at
much less cost to the economy and the economy of neighboring
countries if they had been addressed in a more timely manner."
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin issued a statement
expressing his welcome to the IMF package as a "significant step"
toward establishing economic stability in Thailand, "which is
important to the United States and the rest of the international
community."
</P>
<P>
The United States is prepared to participate in a short-term,
multilateral bridging facility, if needed and under appropriate
conditions, to provide liquidity in support of Thailand's program,
Rubin expressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
