<HEADLINE> France Calls on U.S. to Give U.N. Means of Action </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 21 (Xinhua) -- France today called on the United
States to give the United Nations both financial and political
means to take actions worldwide, especially in flash spots such as
Africa.
</P>
<P>
French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine made the appeal during a
meeting with U.S. ambassador to the United Nations, Bill
Richardson, who was on a European tour to inform the "state of
reflection" at the U.S. administration and the U.S. Congress over
the relations between Washington and the world body.
</P>
<P>
French Foreign Ministry spokesman Yves Doutriaux said that
Vedrine and Richardson discussed a range of issues, including
reform of the U.N., the enlargement of the U.N. Security Council,
the debt the United States owes to the U.N., and a reevaluation of
the quotas shared by different countries in financing the U.N.
budget.
</P>
<P>
Vedrine recalled the position of the European Union that the
United States should pay to the U.N. its 1 billion dollar
contribution arrears, said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The United States and Europe also agree that the Security
Council should be enlarges, but they differ over the number of new
members.
</P>
<P>
The French foreign minister also suggested an reinforcement of
cooperation with the United States within the U.N. in helping end
the conflicts in Africa, said Doutriaux. 
</P>
