<HEADLINE> Botswana Bans Meat From Zamibia, Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Botswana has banned meat
and all by-products entering the country from Zambia and Zimbabwe
following an outbreak of foot and mouth disease in the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
Botswanan farmers must ensure their livestock move away from
the common borders, the Southern African Broadcasting Association
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Botswanan President Ketumile Masire has reportedly called on
customs officials to step up searches on vehicles crossing the
borders.
</P>
<P>
Foot and mouth disease was reported in Zimbabwe two weeks ago
in Chiredzi, some 495 km from the capital of Harare.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwean authorities said that the animal disease in the
area had been under control and more veterinary officers had been
assigned to speed up vaccination.
</P>
<P>
Welbourne Madzima, Zimbabwe's director of veterinary services,
said earlier that an average of 60,000 cattle were being
vaccinated daily in the affected area. 
</P>
