<HEADLINE> S. Leone Junta Refused to Attend ECOWAS Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The military junta in Sierra
Leone received another snub from the international community
today when it was refused to attend a forthcoming sub-regional
summit.
</P>
<P>
According to the British Broadcast Company today, the Foreign
Ministry of the junta, which seized power in the May 25 coup, has
asked for participation in the summit of heads of state and
government of the Economic Community of West African States
(ECOWAS) scheduled for next week in Abuja, Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
To reply the request, the ECOWAS Executive Secretariat today
informed the junta that relevant documentation needed for the
meeting had been given to the toppled civilian government of
President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that this decision to invite Kabbah's
legitimate government to the summit was made in accordance with a
recent meeting of the ECOWAS Committee of Four on Sierra Leone in
Conakry, Guinea, in June which specified that no country should
recognize the junta in Freetown.
</P>
<P>
The Executive Secretariat further said it would continue to
call on the implementation of this and other decisions that might
be passed at the ECOWAS authority.  
</P>
</TEXT>
