<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Not to Participate in Conference on Panama Canal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations would
not participate in the conference on the Panama Canal to be held
in September, a UN spokesman said here today.
</P>
<P>
When answering a question on the UN's stand on the coming
conference known as "Universal Congress on the Panama Canal" at
the noon press briefing today, Brandt Juan Carlos, associate
spokesman for the UN secretary general, said that the UN had made
the decision because Panama had invited Taiwan authorities to be
present at the conference.
</P>
<P>
Asked about the reason of the new decision since the General
Assembly had adopted a resolution on the conference, Carlos said,
"The UN has decided not to participate in the conference due to
the fact that if we do, we will be in a certain way violating
another General Assembly resolution that recognizes the People's
Republic of China as the sole representative of China in the
United Nations," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We understand that Panama has invited Taiwan to be present at
the conference. They will be there as special guests of the
government of Panama," he said.
</P>
<P>
"It is not prudent for the United Nations and the United
Nations system to be part of this conference in those
circumstances," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
When asked whether China had asked the UN to withdraw from the
conference, Carlos said that it was not a question of China asking
the United Nations to withdraw from the conference. It was a
question of the UN being consistent with the mandate of the General
Assembly on this question, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
"It is true the General Assembly originally had welcomed this
event in Panama. It is also true that the United Nations has to be
consistent with regard to something as delicate as the question of
membership of a member state," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
