<HEADLINE> US Prepares to Impose Duty Fines on Japanese Companies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The United States is posed to
impose stiff duties on supercomputers made by two Japanese
companies for violating an international anti-dumping agreement,
the U.S. Department of Commerce announced here today.
</P>
<P>
The department said the tariffs amount to 454 percent on
supercomputers made by NEC Corp. and 173 percent on those
manufactured by Fujitsu Ltd.
</P>
<P>
The case is forwarded to the International Trade Commission for
an August 27 hearing to determine whether the companies' actions
hurt U.S. businesses.
</P>
<P>
In a preliminary decision in March, the Commerce Department
said NEC violated anti-dumping regulations by trying to sell the
U.S. government four supercomputers for the price of one.
</P>
<P>
Cray Research Inc., a U.S. company, filed a complaint with the
government in July 1996 after NEC won a contract for government
weather forecasting computers with the National Center for
Atmospheric Research in Boulder, Colo., an affiliate of the
federally funded National Science Foundation.
</P>
<P>
Cray said the 35 million U.S. dollar price tag on NEC's
computers was less than one-fourth of their fair value.
</P>
<P>
But NEC responded that the price was not only greater than cost
of manufacturing the machines but that it included a profit
margin. 
</P>
</TEXT>
