<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Helps Cameroun Build 30 Primary Schools </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDE, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Japan will grant Cameroun 5
billion CFA Francs (Approximately 10 million U.S. dollars) to
build primary shools under an agreement signed here today.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement which was signed by Jean Gaukou,
minister-delegate of the Ministry of Economy and Finance and the
Japanese ambassador to Cameroun, the money will be used to build
30 primary shools and 200 classrooms in Yaounde and the country's
economic capital Douala.
</P>
<P>
After the signing ceremony, Gaukou highlighted the excellent
relations existing between the governments of Cameroun and Japan.
</P>
<P>
He also emphasized that the new contribution from Japan to
finance projects in Cameroun's education sector falls in line
with the Camerounian government's policy to fight against
illiteracy in the country, which is seen as a serious obstacle to
achieve sustainable development.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the 5 billion Francs offered today, Gaukou
said, the Japanese government had in the past two years given
some 6 billion cfa Francs to his country to finance portable
water supply projects in 10 rural areas in the country.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Japanese ambassador to Cameroun Takeru Sasaguchi
said his country's choice to finance projects in the education
sector in sub-Sahara Africa in general and Cameroun in particular
is to contribute in a significant way to ameliorate basic
education which is seen as an essential factor to achieve social
economic development in all countries.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese ambassador reviewed that since 1988, his country
has financed projects in the domain of education, health and
rural development worth 92 billion CFA Francs in Cameroun.
</P>
</TEXT>
