<HEADLINE> People's Insurance Reports Marginal Growth In Premiums </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 22 (Xinhua) -- The People's Insurance Company
of China (PICC), the country's largest insurer, saw a 50 percent
rise in premiums in the first half of the year to 42.8 billion
yuan (five billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Ma Yongwei, president and general manager, said that PICC's
total assets exceed 100 billion yuan (12 billion US dollars) and
it now has nearly 74 percent of China's insurance market and he
noted that "it is because of China's continuous reforms and
opening-up and its steady economic growth that PICC has expanded
so quickly."
</P>
<P>
The company now has about 400 types of insurance services, and
about 600,000 Chinese enterprises and 100 million families have
bought property and life insurence policies.
</P>
<P>
Ma said PICC was successfully reshaped into a corporation last
year and it set up three subsidiaries for life and property
insurance. Each of them plays a major role in their respective
fields, insurance experts said.
</P>
<P>
They held that the move was intended to face the increasing
challenge from competitors and to consolidate its leading position
in China's insurance market.
</P>
<P>
PICC has paid a total of 150 billion yuan in claims by Chinese
policy-holders in the past five years, Ma said, and "PICC now
functions well as China's largest state-owned insurer in
safeguarding the country's economic growth and social stability."
</P>
<P>
PICC is also seeking to extend its business share in the
booming insurance market in the coming years to maintain its
leading status, Ma added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
