<HEADLINE> Turkey Rejects OECD Investigation of Money </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Turkey has rebuffed an
anti-money laundering investigation request from the Paris-based
Organization for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD),
local newspaper Daily News reported today.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Financial Ministry officials who declined to be
named told the newspaper that Turkey has taken effective
measures to crack down on money laundering in the country.
</P>
<P>
"Turkey has been implementing the needed reregulations related
to the money laundering. Under these circumstances, there is no
need for the OECD to make research in Turkey," the officials
said.
</P>
<P>
However, the OECD complains that money laundering conducted by
illegal organizations has been rampant in Turkey in recent years.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting held in June, the OECD's Financial Activity
Mission Group urged the Turkish government to clean up the money
laundering activities with tough steps, saying it would launch
an investigation in Turkey if necessary.
</P>
<P>
Turkish financial experts have been reportedly asked by the
government to start an investigation into such activities, and
an expert team will submit their report to the authorities by
October 1. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
