<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1530 GMT, August 22 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK -- Thai Prime Minister Chavalit Yongchaiyudh, today met
Cambodian Co-Defense Ministers, Gen. Tea Banh and Gen. Tea
Chamrath, and discussed the situation at the Thai-Cambodian
border, where tens of thousands of Cambodian refugees have crossed
into Thailand.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, the two sides exchanged views on
establishing a joint committee to solve problems at the border.
</P>
<P>
The Cambodian ministers told Chavalit, who is concurrently Thai
 defense minister, that fighting in Cambodia was easing and they
called on Cambodian refugees to return home.
</P>
<P>
They promised to guarantee the refugees' safe return.
</P>
<P>
About 40,000 Cambodians have fled to Thailand following heavy
fighting in Cambodia between government forces and those loyal to
prince Norodom Ranarridh in areas opposite Thailand's northeastern
Surin Province.
</P>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR -- China cannot accept the recent open remarks by
Japanese Chief Cabinet Secretary Seiroku Kajiyama of expanding
the scope of the Japan-U.S. Security Treaty to the Taiwan Straits.
</P>
<P>
Li made the remarks in response to a participant's question
after delivering a speech on good-neighborly ties at a welcoming
meeting hosted by Malaysia's Institute of Diplomatic and Foreign
Relations.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the remarks pose severe interference into China's
internal affairs, as Taiwan is an inalienable part of China.
</P>
<P>
This is the internationally acknowledged fact and has been
explicitly recognized in the joint communiques on the
establishment of diplomatic ties between China and Japan, and
between China and the United States, the premier stressed.
</P>
<P>
"The Chief Cabinet Secretary's remarks have arose
dissatisfaction not only among the Chinese people, but also among
the people in Southeast Asian countries," Li said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
