<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taiwanese Scholars Opposes Westerners' Attempt to Split Tibet (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Three Taiwanese scholars
attending the ongoing 1997 Beijing Seminar on Tibetan Studies held
that some Western people who advocate separatism for Tibet have
inherited an imperialist mindset and are only acting in their own
interests.
</P>
<P>
Lin Kuan Chun, a history professor with National Chengchi
University in Taiwan, said Tibet has had a close relationship
with the central government since the Tang Dynasty (618-907).
</P>
<P>
Tibetan culture has closer ties with the Central Plains
areas of China than with the neighboring countries of Tibet.
</P>
<P>
"Tibetan Buddhism used to be influenced by the religion from
India, but Tibetan people did not accept too much Indian culture.
Religion is only a small part of culture," Lin said.
</P>
<P>
"Some Westerners are using dual standards toward Tibet," the
professor said, noting that Britain consists of several islands
with different cultures, and the United States includes Alaska,
which is inhabited by Eskimos, in its territory.
</P>
<P>
"This indicates that a country can be composed of many ethnic
groups, so why do some people in the west only want to separate
Tibet?" he queried.
</P>
<P>
Gene J. Y Chang, professor with the Institute of Nationality
Studies of National Chengchi University of Taiwan, holds a similar
view, noting that cultural and geographical differences should not
be used as an excuse to split a country.
</P>
<P>
Politically, some government officials in the West have
attempted to split China because they are afraid of China's
growing strength. In recent years, there has been some noise about
the "China Threat" theory in the world, some western powers fear
that their interests will be harmed if China remains a united and
strong country, he said.
</P>
<P>
"In particular, some people in Western countries do not want to
see the economic prosperity and other achievements in China's
interior areas over the recent years," the professor said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970822.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taiwanese Scholars Opposes Westerners' Attempt to Split Tibet (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
On the other hand, some non-governmental organizations in the
West are fed up with modern life, for they have seen the demise of
rare wild animals, dwindling forest populations, pollution, the
lack of civility between people, and the change of traditional way
of life and customs among people of minority ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
Gene J. Y Chang labels this "post-modernism," saying that these
people want to return to a simpler way of life, such as the type
they had before the modernization of society.
</P>
<P>
"They cannot find such a life at home, so they find the East
and find old Tibet, discovering a piece of pure land over
there. The more the central government helps Tibet and Tibet
becomes more modernized, the more the Westerners oppose and
curse," he said.
</P>
<P>
"They do not keep in mind that Tibetan people also have the
right to lead a modern and civilized life," the professor said.
</P>
<P>
Veteran Tibetan studies scholar Thomas C. W. Lu, a 72-year-old
professor with the Chinese Culture University of Taiwan, shares
the view that the Western nations, including the United States,
in their attempt to split Tibet do not want to see a strong China.
</P>
<P>
"Some people in the West say there are no human rights in
Tibet, but according to my findings there, Tibetan people have
more human rights than they did before the liberation of Tibet,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Lu graduated from Fudan University of Shanghai in 1948 and then
taught in Taiwan. He enrolled in a Tibetan studies program in 1965
and obtained a Ph.D. in Japan.
</P>
<P>
Ordinary Tibetans had little knowledge about human rights under
the rigid religious system in old Tibet, he noted. The serfs were
oppressed but they regarded this as their fate and did not think
of rebelling.
</P>
<P>
Now, human rights conditions in Tibet have improved greatly, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The professor has made inspection tours in Lhasa, Xigaze and
some other places in Tibet. "I think the Tibetan people are free
to have their own religious belief," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
