<HEADLINE> Export-Led Growth Urged in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 22 (Xinhua) -- The expansion of Zimbabwe's
manufacturing sector will have to be export-led to enable local
companies to compete in the lucrative eastern and southern Africa
regional markets, a cabinet minister has said.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Herbert Murerwa told the latest issue of
Commerce Magazine that the Southern Africa Development Community
(SADC) and Common Market for Eastern and Southern Africa
(COMESA), presently valued at about 150 billion U.S. Dollars,
were indispensable stepping stones for exports.
</P>
<P>
''Regional companies in general and local enterprises in
particular need to make a special effort to identify market
segments in the region and develop products and services tailored
to the needs of these markets,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
He urged the local business community to take advantage of the
enabling environment that governments are striving to create
through SADC and COMESA.
</P>
<P>
Local companies, he noted, should be able to compete because
of cultural familiarity, shorter distances and less restrictions,
coupled with efforts being made by member states to facilitate
trade and investment.
</P>
<P>
A major development, he said, was the Democratic Republic of
Congo's (DRC) statement underlining its commitment to economic
reconstruction and institution building.
</P>
<P>
He urged companies to actively prospect for and initiate
projects aligned to the reconstruction process.
</P>
<P>
''More recently, the DRC has unveiled many investment and
trade opportunities which our companies should pursue,'' Murerwa
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
