<HEADLINE> Chinese, Malaysian PMs Satisfied with Bilateral Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Chinese Premier Li
Peng and his Malaysian counterpart Mahathir Mohammad today
expressed their satisfaction over the matured all-round relations
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The two prime ministers met here today, pledging that the two
governments should continue to be active in further promoting such
relations especially in the economic and trade fields.
</P>
<P>
Welcoming the Chinese premier's visit, Mahathir said, "We are
glad to witness the development of very friendly and close
relations between our two countries in recent years."
</P>
<P>
Mahathir hoped that Li's current visit would further strengthen
the friendly relations of cooperation between the two countries,
which would benefit not only the two peoples but also the region
as a whole.
</P>
<P>
Agreeing with Mahathir, Li Peng said the Sino-Malaysian
relations have entered a stage of matured all-round development.
"China is willing to work together with Malaysia for a
long-standing and stable relationship of friendship and
good-neighborliness geared to the 21st century," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Li said that with the joint efforts, the bilateral ties have
made big headway since the establishment of diplomatic relations
between China and Malaysia,.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese premier said that though there have been great
changes in the world and the region, the two sides have treated
and developed the bilateral ties from the strategic height and the
far-sighted angle, ensuring the right direction of the development
of bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
He said that in recent years, the frequent exchanges of
top-level visit between the two countries have built up the mutual
trust and friendship and added new impetus to the development of
the bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
"During your (Mahathir) visit to China last year, our two sides
signed several agreements on economic cooperation, which played a
good role in pushing forward the bilateral economic and trade
cooperation," Li Peng said.
</P>
<P>
Li Peng said that with the further development of economies of
the two countries, there exist market potentials for each other to
tap.
</P>
<P>
"We are willing to explore new ideas and new ways together with
Malaysia to develop economic and trade cooperation so as to
jointly move the bilateral cooperation of mutual benefit to a
newer and broader direction," Li said.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir agreed with Li Peng's view, saying that the Malaysian
government would work with China to that end.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders also agreed to further the increase bilateral
cooperation in the finance sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
