<HEADLINE> China Sentences Men for Railway Tragedy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, August 22 (Xinhua) -- The Guangzhou Railway
Intermediate Court opened today in Changsha, capital of
central-south China's Hunan Province, and sentenced two men
convicted of causing a serious railway tragedy last April.
</P>
<P>
Hao Renzhong was given a life sentence and deprived of all
political rights. Wu Rongzhong was sentenced to 15 years in prison
and stripped of his political rights for five years.
</P>
<P>
The two on April 29 knowingly tampered with a signal control
system and removed a part used to control a rail intersection. The
wrong signal consequently caused the collision of two passenger
trains, in which 126 passengers and railway crew were killed and
45 seriously injured. Damage amounted to 4.15 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with the Law of Railways and the Criminal Law of
the People's Republic of China, the two were charged with
destroying a transport facility.
</P>
<P>
Two other men, both associates of Hao and Wu, were sentenced
today for dereliction of duty, receiving a prison term of two to
three years with a reprieve of three to four years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
