<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Diverges on New Defense Guidelines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Japan's ruling Liberal Democratic
Party (LDP) and its two allies, the Social Democratic Party (SDP)
and the New Party Sakigake, failed to hammer out a common view
today on the new Japan-U.S. defense guidelines.
</P>
<P>
Differences between the SDP and the LDP, led by Prime Minister
Ryutaro Hashimoto, remain over the definition of "areas
surrounding Japan."
</P>
<P>
At a meeting of policy-makers from the tripartite ruling camp,
the SDP reiterated its position that the Taiwan Straits be
excluded from areas subject to the proposed new guidelines.
</P>
<P>
But Taku Yamazaki, chairman of the LDP's Political Affairs
Investigation Committee, argued that "emergencies in surrounding
areas" referred to those which would threaten Japan's peace and
security.
</P>
<P>
They are defined in accordance with the nature of the
occurrences, not geographical concepts, Yamazaki said.
</P>
<P>
Noting that the new guidelines were designed under the
framework of the Japan-U.S. security treaty, Yamazaki said the
definition of the Far East was important when talking about Japan
providing logistical and noncombatant support to the U.S. military.
</P>
<P>
The LDP still claims that the Far East, as defined under the
security treaty, refers to areas from the Philippines to the
north, including Taiwan and the Korean Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
The issue of how to define the areas surrounding Japan has been
in the spotlight since Chief Cabinet Secretary Seiroku Kajiyama
said on a Sunday TV talk show that the new defense guidelines
would cover emergencies in the Taiwan Straits.
</P>
<P>
Kajiyama's remarks triggered strong criticism from China. His
words appeared to signal an attempt to interfere in China's
internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here believe that today's remark by Yamazaki showed
the Japanese government's resolution to reach an agreement that
the new guidelines should include the Taiwan Straits.
</P>
<P>
The new guidelines are intended to replace the 1978 Japan-U.S.
defense cooperation guidelines, and to pave the way for Japan to
provide a broad range of logistic and noncombatant support to the
U.S. military in case of emergencies "in areas surrounding Japan."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970822.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Poetry Reading For Deng Xiaoping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, August 22 (Xinhua) -- At a stage performance last
night Shanghai artists recited a 3,000-line-poem, "Song for Deng
Xiaoping", to celebrate late Deng's 93rd birthday, which falls on
today.
</P>
<P>
Accompanied by the Shanghai Opera House orchestra, 15
well-known Shanghai artists, representing three generations, read
the poem's six-parts: "Prelude," "Chief Architect," "The Road of
Exploration," "Economic Reform," "Great Changes of China," and
"Hong Kong, Oh, Hong Kong."
</P>
<P>
Sun Daolin, a famous artist, commented, "I am 76 years old. I
have witnessed China's rise and fall in history, China could never
have been so strong if it weren't for Deng's theory." This was the
fourth time for Sun to read the poem in less than a year.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai Orient Television, one of the sponsors of the party,
broadcast a tape of the party tonight. There is also a web site on
the Internet so that surfers worldwide can appreciate the poem on
their computer screens.
</P>
<P>
It was written last year by the Shanghai poet Gui Xinghua, who
is famous for his poetry with political themes. It describes the
glorious life of the great man. It has been published and recorded
on audio cassette and MTV and has been well received by people.
</P>
<P>
Deng passed away in February of this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
