<DOCNO> XIE19970822.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Li Peng on Domestic Situation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 22 (Xinhua) -- The life style and belief
of more than 18 million Muslims in China are fully respected,
visiting Chinese Premier Li Peng said here today.
</P>
<P>
There are more than 30,000 mosques in China, and in places
where Muslims gather to live, autonomous regions, prefectures and
townships have been set up, he said.
</P>
<P>
Li made the remarks in response to participants' questions
after delivering a speech on good-neighborly ties at a welcoming
meeting hosted by Malaysia's Institute of Diplomatic and Foreign
Relations.
</P>
<P>
There are 55 ethnic minority groups in China, whose population
account for nine percent of the country's total of 1.2 billion,
the premier said.
</P>
<P>
When asked about protection of the rights of women and children
in China, Li said in 1995, over 40,000 women worldwide came to
Beijing to attend the 4th World Conference on Women.
</P>
<P>
This enabled them to have an extensive understanding of the
circumstances of Chinese women and children, and China's efforts
to protect the rights of women and children were widely
appreciated, the premier stated.
</P>
<P>
It is a fundamental policy of China to ensure the men and women
on an equal footing, Li said, adding the country has worked out
respective guidelines to guarantee the development of the women
and children.
</P>
<P>
In China, women cherish equal rights with men and their
political status is growing continuously, and their political
participation is obviously improving, he said.
</P>
<P>
Among the 3,000 deputies to the National People's Congress, Li
went on, women constitute over 20 percent of the total and women
cadres make up 33 percent of the total cadres working in
governmental institutions and enterprises.
</P>
<P>
And women account for 38.6 percent of the workers in township
enterprises, he said, adding the women's economic status is also
growing, with their income increasing and education improving.
</P>
<P>
Some 98.63 percent of the school-aged girls can go to school,
he added.
</P>
<P>
The premier noted that the children's rights are also
guaranteed, with a nine-year compulsory education system and a
pre-school education for them.
</P>
<P>
In the country, over 80 percent of the country's territory,
including the rural areas, practice disease immunity and
prevention medical services for children, the premier added.
</P>
<P>
He explained that some common children diseases, such as
varicella and infantile paralysis, have been eliminated on the
whole.
</P>
<P>
However, this does not mean to say that there has been no
incidents of child abuse, Li said, adding this violates the
Chinese law and will be punished according to the criminal law.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese nationals have developed a very dear feeling toward
the family life and thus their families are on a rather solid
basis, which do good to the children's growth and education, Li
added.
</P>
<P>
When asked about some analysts' arguments that China has become
the world's second largest economic power, Li said this comment is
an exaggerated prediction on China's economy.
</P>
<P>
As China has a huge population, its per capita GNP is listed at
the back row of the world, he said.
</P>
<P>
Li said the per capita GNP of Malaysians is registered at 3,000
U.S. dollars, and China has not yet reached this level.
</P>
<P>
If China hopes to become a middle-level developed nation, it
needs some 30 years of arduous efforts, the premier added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970822.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Plant Closed, Millions of Pounds of Meat Recalled in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 22 (Xinhua) -- A Nebraska meat-processing
plant has been closed and expanded its recall of ground beef to 25
million pounds after Federal investigators found evidence that far
more meat might be contaminated by hazardous bacteria than
originally suspected last week.
</P>
<P>
E. coli bacteria contamination originated outside the plant at
the slaughterhouse, but the massive recall is needed because of
problems with meat handling, record keeping and safety testing,
Agriculture Department officials said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Columbus, Nebraska, plant will not open until the company
has adopted "far more stringent safety standards that we have
specifically laid out for them based on what we have found in our
investigation," Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman said.
</P>
<P>
Recalls were announced last week by Hudson Foods of Rogers
after health officials in Colorado traced the illnesses of more
than a dozen people to hamburger patties they ate in early June.
</P>
<P>
It first recalled 20,000 pounds of meat, then another 20,000,
and expanded to 1.2 million pounds last Friday.
</P>
<P>
E. coli is a potentially deadly bacteria that often gets into
food through contact with fecal matter. It causes severe diarrhea,
cramps and dehydration.
</P>
<P>
Every year in the United States, bacteria in meat, poultry,
seafood, eggs, fruit and vegetables kill as many as 9,000 people
and sicken millions, the New York Times said today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
