<HEADLINE> Oil Price Hike Decision to Be Approved Soon in India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 22 (Xinhua) -- A minimum of 10 to 15 percent
hike in the prices of petroleum products is likely to be approved
by the Indian cabinet which is scheduled to meet here tomorrow,
Press Trust of India (PTI) said today.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet was entrusted with the responsibility of taking a
final decision on the long pending issue of hike in prices of
petroleum products when the United Front Steering Committee gave
the green signal to Prime Minister Inder Kumar Gujral on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
After a one-hour meeting on Thursday night, the steering
committee said it had left the decision on the issue to Gujral and
his cabinet.
</P>
<P>
The oil price hike, hanging fire in the last six months because
of sharp differences between the left parties and other parties in
the United Front Coalition, has become imperative with the deficit
caused by subsidies to petroleum products burgeoning day by day.
</P>
<P>
The deficit, which has touched a staggering 220 billion rupees
(about 6.29 billion U.S. dollars), is projected to go well beyond
the originally projected 245 billion rupees (about 7.00 billion
dollars) by the end of the current fiscal year (from April 1997 to
march 1998) as it is mounting by 320 million rupees (about 9.14
million dollars) a day.  
</P>
</TEXT>
