<HEADLINE> France Condemns Reinforcement of Arms in Congo Republic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 22 (Xinhua) -- France today condemned the
resurgence of weapons and armaments in the Congo Republic by both
sides in the conflict, and once again called on them to stop
fighting.
</P>
<P>
"The reinforcement of armaments ... is in total contradiction
with the spirit of Libreville. We urge the Congolese parties to
respect their ceasefire and conclude without delay a political
solution," French Foreign Ministry spokesman Yves Doutriaux said.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the two warring sides of the Congo Republic,
President Pascal Lissouba and former president General Denis
Sassou N'Guesso, signed a ceasefire agreement in the Gabonese
capital of Libreville on July 13.
</P>
<P>
But soon afterwards they broke the truce by intensifying
fighting in Brazzaville, the capital city, and in other provinces,
killing at least 4,000 people so far.
</P>
<P>
"It is inadmissible that the Congolese parties should attempt
to look for a military solution to the crisis, despising the
suffering of the people," the French spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed support for Gabonese President Omar Bongo's peace
proposal for the Congo Republic, which sets precise roles for the
country's president and prime minister in preparing for the future
presidential election.
</P>
<P>
The newest proposal by Bongo calls for the deployment of a
United Nations peace-keeping force in the war-stricken country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
