<DOCNO> XIE19970822.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Accelerating State-Owned Enterprise Reforms (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
State-owned enterprises are still taking a "leading position"
in energy, transportation, post and telecommunications,
metallurgy, chemical and automotive industries, and in
machinery and electronics, Chen said.
</P>
<P>
A large number of efficient state-owned enterprises have gained
force through intense market competitions. And although they are a
mere 0.44 percent of the state-owned industrial sector in terms of
numbers, the 512 enterprises that are given priority in central
government financial aid have 43.7 percent of the total sales
income and 65.85 percent of the profits.
</P>
<P>
However, the state-owned sector still faces problems like a
lack of balance in the industrial structure, welfare problems for
employees, and slow technical progress, Chen explained, so the
country will speed up structural reforms in the coming years,
while establishing the socialist market economy.
</P>
<P>
In the next phase of reforms, the central government will shift
focus onto a "modern enterprise system" and adjusting the
industrial structure, and will use bankruptcies and mergers.
</P>
<P>
The re-employment scheme, which is regarded as an effective
way to ease unemployment pressures from the enterprise reforms,
will be given even greater importance.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the country will urge enterprises to step up their
reorganization, and to effectively improve their management
methods and increase technological improvements, Vice-Minister
Chen said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
