<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Historical Records Prove Tibet Is Inseparable Part of China (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Scholars attending the ongoing
1997 Beijing Seminar on Tibetan Studies said there is concrete
evidence that Tibet has been part of China's territory since
ancient times.
</P>
<P>
Based on historical records and latest archeological findings,
the scholars pointed out: "Any words or activities to advocate the
independence of Tibet are groundless."
</P>
<P>
Tubo (the ancient word for Tibet) was an area under the
jurisdiction of Xuanzhengyuan, the Commission for Buddhist and
Tibetan Affairs, during the Yuan Dynasty (1271-1368), said Wang
Gui, a research fellow with the Chinese Military Academy of
Sciences.
</P>
<P>
"It was on the same level as other provinces, so it was
called 'Tubo Province'," Wang noted.
</P>
<P>
He said the term "the Province of Tibet" can be seen on page
172 of The Travels of Marco Polo, published by the Macmillan
Company of the United States in 1927. It also appears on page 100
of The Travels of Marco Polo, published by John Company of New
York in 1948.
</P>
<P>
On another page of the English book, Marco Polo wrote: "The
Province of Tibet is also under the jurisdiction of the Great
Khan."
</P>
<P>
Wang Gui said that the Sakya Lineage, written in the 17th
century, has been one of the fundamental sources for the study of
Tibetan history by scholars at home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
In the sixth section of Part Three of the book, one passage
reads: "There are a total of eleven provinces under the
jurisdiction of Mongol Emperor Kublai. Although the number of
households in the three Tubo regions could not meet the demand of
a province, it was regarded as a province because here was the
place where the ruling lama (Phagpa) took his residence and
preached Buddhism."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970822.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Historical Records Prove Tibet Is Inseparable Part of China (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Although the authors of the two books were from different
countries, used different languages and wrote about different
topics, they were "identical in the statement that Tibet was a
provincial administrative region during the Yuan Dynasty, Wang Gui
said.
</P>
<P>
Chiu Wen Lu, a professor with the Chinese Culture University in
Taiwan, said the relationship of subordination between Tibet and
the central government was formed naturally a long time ago.
</P>
<P>
"What is important is that the formation of the relationship
resulted from various religious sects and local forces in Tibet,
which vied with each other and willingly relied on the central
government for the sake of keeping their own existence and
development, safeguarding their vested interests, and balancing
the power of different sects," the professor said.
</P>
<P>
Chang Fengxuan, a research fellow with the Institute of
Nationality Studies of the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences,
said that originally the Dalai Lama was one of the many incarnate
lamas of the Gelugpa sect, rather than a hierarch of all sects of
Tibetan Buddhism or a leader of the regime which merged religious
and secular rule.
</P>
<P>
It was not until 1653 that the Qing Dynasty (1644-1911)
government conferred the title of Dalai Lama on Lozang Gyatso, the
fifth successor of the Gelugpa sect, and thus established Dalai
Lama's political position in Tibet.
</P>
<P>
The local regime which merged clerical and secular rule in the
history of Tibet was not simply under the command of a certain
religious sect, it had to take orders from central authorities, he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970822.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Historical Records Prove Tibet Is Inseparable Part of China (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The successive governments of the Republic of China were always
in contact with Tibet; the Republic of China set up an office in
Lhasa; the international community recognized that Tibet was a
political entity under the sovereignty of China; and it has never
been an independent state.
</P>
<P>
According to the Code of Great Qing, the Resident Minister was
the highest executive in charge of Tibetan administrative,
military, financial and foreign affairs, and also acted as an
imperial envoy in charge of the administration of Tibetan
religious affairs.
</P>
<P>
That indicates the Qing Court directly ruled Tibet at that
time, said Zhang Yuxin, deputy director of the China Institute of
Cultural Relics.
</P>
<P>
The Qing Court put the system of reincarnation under control
of law by devising the method of drawing lots from a gold urn,
according to Huang Hao, a research fellow with the Institute of
Nationality Studies of the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences.
</P>
<P>
This showed that the Qing government had the final say about
the reincarnation selection process, Huang said. Formally, it was
an important institution installed by the Qing government to
administrate Tibetan Buddhism, but its profound contents reflected
the political authority of the central government, he added.
</P>
<P>
The scholars pointed out that there is no historical support
for advocating Tibet Independence. History has proved time and
again that only while in the embrace of the motherland can Tibet
achieve sound and rapid development, an improved living standard,
and more freedom. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970822.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Deplores Lack of Western Coordination on Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 22 (Xinhua) -- France today deplored the lack of
coordination and cooperation among Western countries in their
reaction to the tension in Kenya.
</P>
<P>
Ambassadors of 13 Western nations signed an appeal in Nairobi
Thursday calling for political reform in Kenya.
</P>
<P>
France did not sign the appeal because it was initiated outside
the European Union, French Foreign Ministry spokesman Yves
Doutriaux said.
</P>
<P>
"Concerning the taking of a position by countries of the
European Union, we aren't in the habit of rallying ourselves
without concertation to texts elaborated outside the European
Union," he said.
</P>
<P>
The appeal, jointly issued by the ambassadors of the United
States, Switzerland, Canada, Japan and a number of EU countries,
condemned the violence in Mombasa, Kenya's second largest city and
key Indian Ocean port, and urged the Kenyan government and the
opposition to start a dialogue.
</P>
<P>
It also urged the Kenyan government to carry out "necessary
reforms to ensure free and just elections."
</P>
<P>
France condemned the violence in Mombasa and the Coast
Province. It lasted for nine days and has so far claimed 40
lives. France also appealed to both sides of the conflict to
refrain from resorting to force, said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Paris also echoed the appeal by the 13 countries by urging the
Kenyan government to initiate talks with the opposition on
political reforms that would allow "free and transparent"
elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
