<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Li Peng on Japan-U.S. Security Alliance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 22 (Xinhua) -- China cannot accept the
recent open remarks by Japanese Chief Cabinet Secretary Seiroku
Kajiyama of expanding the scope of the Japan-U.S. Security Treaty
to the Taiwan Straits.
</P>
<P>
Li made the remarks in response to a participant's question
after delivering a speech on good-neighborly ties at a welcoming
meeting hosted by Malaysia's Institute of Diplomatic and Foreign
Relations.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the remarks pose severe interference into China's
internal affairs, as Taiwan is an inalienable part of China.
</P>
<P>
This is the internationally acknowledged fact and has been
explicitly recognized in the joint communiques on the
establishment of diplomatic ties between China and Japan, and
between China and the United States, the premier stressed.
</P>
<P>
"The Chief Cabinet Secretary's remarks have arose
dissatisfaction not only among the Chinese people, but also among
the people in Southeast Asian countries," Li said.
</P>
<P>
"I don't mean to comment another country in this host country,
and the speech venue is a Japanese hotel Nikko," he said, adding
"As you raise this question, I would certainly make clear our
principled stand."
</P>
<P>
In general, the Sino-Japanese ties are good, Li said, adding
"We are willing to develop normal friendly relations of
cooperation with Japan, as this is conducive to regional peace and
stability."
</P>
<P>
"However, we should guard against acts by the few Japanese
militarists and right wing forces to undermine the China-Japan
relations," Li added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
