<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-22 13:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Rebuffs Accusation Against N. Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Turkey today categorically
rejected U.N. Security Council president's accusations that
the second round of the Cyprus talks collapsed due to Turkish
Cypriots' preconditions.
</P>
<P>
A Foreign Ministry written statement announced that Turkey
could not agree with the remarks made by British Permanent
Representative to the U.N., Sir Jone Weston, which accuses
Turkish Cypriots of impeding the peace tallks.
</P>
<P>
Weston had reportedly said in a speech that the Turkish
Cypriot side blocked the substantive process "by bringing
preconditions to the table."
</P>
<P>
"The British representative's statement failed to reflect the
truth of the second round of Cyprus peace talks in the Swiss
town of Montreux," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktas and Cypriot President
Glafcos Clerides held peace talks in Switzerland last week under
the auspices of the U.N., as a continuation of their first
round negotiations at Troutbeck, near New York last month.
</P>
<P>
However, the second round of talks did not produce concrete
fruits since neither side was ready to make concessions on a
number of sensitive issues.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Foreign Ministry statement stressed that the
Cypriot government's plan to apply for full EU membership on
behalf of the whole divided island is the real barrier to
the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission's recommendation, which included Cyprus
into the ranks of prospective candidates for EU membership,
has also produced a negative impact on the slightly fruitful
Troutbeck talks, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that Denktas just did what the Turkish
Cypriot authorities instructed him to do.
</P>
<P>
Denktas himself also denied Weston's remarks at a reception
in Nicosia, accusing the British representative of openly
shielding the Cypriot government.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has long remained divided since 1974 when the
Turkey sent troops and took over the northern third of the
island nation following a failed coup seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. and international community has been making efforts
for years in a bid to solve the protracted problem, but no
tangible results has been achieved so far.
</P>
<P>
Both Greece and Turkey station troops on the eastern
Mediterranean island which is divided into northern Turkish
community and southern Greek community. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
