<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Envoy in Angola </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, August 22 (Xinhua) -- The American government believes
that peace process in Angola will succeed, despite the problems
faced by the rival sides, a visiting U.S. official said today.
</P>
<P>
Paul Hare, special envoy of U.S. President Bill Clinton, who
arrived here for a week-long visit, said meetings between Angolan
President Eduardo Dos Santos and Jonas Savimbi, chairman of the
rebel UNITA movement, will help get over the current dilemma.
</P>
<P>
Hare is in the limelight of the media since his visit is aimed
at conveying Washington's stand on the situation in Angola to
leaders of both sides so as to push forward the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Hare refused to comment on the resolutions of sanctions that
the U. N. security council is going to impose next week on the
National Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) for
its refusal to implement the Lusaka Peace Protocol signed in
November 1994.
</P>
<P>
The Lusaka accord stipulates that UNITA should be totally
disarmed and turn into a political party, its radio becomes a
media organ on a non-party basis and state power should be
restored in its occupied zones in cooperation with the
government.
</P>
<P>
The current dilemma results from the fact that UNITA has been
slow in taking actions to implement the articles outlined by the
Lusaka Peace Pact. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
