<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Inflation Hits 6.5 Percent in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 22 (Xinhua) -- A surge in the prices of
vegetables pushed Hong Kong's inflation rate higher in July,
official figures showed today.
</P>
<P>
The Census and Statistics Department today released the
Consumer Price Index (CPI) figures for the first month after the
handover.
</P>
<P>
The year-on-year rate of increase in the CPI (A), was 6.5
percent in July, higher than that of 5.4 percent in June.
</P>
<P>
CPI (A) covers 50 percent of households in Hong Kong whose
monthly expenditures are between 3,900 and 16,000 HK dollars (503
to 2,065 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The year-on-year rates of increase in the CPI (B) and Hang Seng
CPI were also higher than in June -- 6.2 percent against 5.6
percent for the CPI (B) and 6.6 percent against 5.9 percent for
the Hang Seng CPI.
</P>
<P>
The Composite CPI, which is compiled based on the combined
expenditure pattern of households covered by the three
sub-indices, showed an 6.4 percent increase in July, higher than
that of 5.6 percent in June.
</P>
<P>
The department attributed the higher inflation rate to a surge
in the prices of vegetables.
</P>
<P>
Due to the prolonged rainy weather, the prices of vegetables
soared by over 60 percent in July, the highest rate of increase
recorded within a single month over the past two decades. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970822.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macao Foreign Trade Up in 1st 6 Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Both imports and exports in the
first six months of the year in Macao rose considerably from the
same period last year, latest statistics show.
</P>
<P>
Figures released by the Macao Census and Statistics Department
show that Macao's imports for the first half of the year reached
8.327 billion patacas (about 1.054 billion US dollars), up nine
percent from the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The value of exported goods hit 7.792 billion patacas (about
986 million US dollars), up 13 percent.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the trade deficit was recorded at 535 million
patacas (about 67.72 million US dollars), down 28.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
The export of textile products and garments, which accounted
for 84.2 percent of all exports, rose 20.7 percent; While the
export of non-textile products, including machinery, equipment,
footwear and cement, dropped 15.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
Macao's main export market focuses on the European Union and
the United States, which bought 76.2 percent of Macao exported
goods.
</P>
<P>
The Asia-Pacific market bought 10 percent less goods from Macao
 during the first six months. The exports to this region only
accounted for 20.6 percent of all.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Macao imported 22 percent more "capital goods", 10.8
 percent more raw materials and semi-finished goods, 10.1 percent
more fuel and lubricative oil, and 0.3 percent more of consumer
goods in the period.
</P>
<P>
The leading import market for Macao is in the Asia-Pacific
region, where Macao bought 80.4 percent of its imports.  
</P>
</TEXT>
