<HEADLINE> Foreign Flu Experts Come to Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Four more influenza experts
from the United States and Japan arrived in Hong Kong overnight to
join a task force investigating how a three-year-old boy died from
a strain previously unseen in humans, a source in the Department
of Health confirmed today.
</P>
<P>
The four experts and a gene investigator from the influenza
branch of the Centers for Disease Control in Atlanta, the United
States, who arrived one day earlier, compose a special team of the
World Health Organization (WHO), the source said, without giving
their names or titles.
</P>
<P>
They will collaborate with members of a special committee set
up by the Department of Health to investigate the new flu strain,
H5N1, which killed the local boy on May 21 at Queen Elizabeth
Hospital after an 11-day illness.
</P>
<P>
It is the first case in the world in which H5N1, a virus
previously known to infect only birds, has infected a human-being, the
source said, noting that the H5N1 strain was similar to one which
killed 4,500 chickens in three farms this spring.  
</P>
</TEXT>
