<DOCNO> XIE19970822.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Developing Distribution System For Chinese Goods (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China now has some 100,000 commodity markets, more than 2,000
of which are produce and farm by-products wholesale markets. Fairs
in urban and rural areas have been growing fast too, with about
85,000 of them by the end of last year, doing 1.5 trillion yuan in
business.
</P>
<P>
Consumer goods have seen large demand but sufficient supplies.
In 1996, sales topped 2.46 trillion yuan, more than a quadruple of
the 1991 figure, an average annual increase of nearly 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
Rapid growth in urban and rural residents' incomes contributed
greatly to the increasing demand. City dwellers' per-capita cost
of living rose from 1,544 yuan in 1991 to 4,377 yuan in 1996, up
nearly six percent in real terms annually.
</P>
<P>
The balance in supply and demand is mainly attributed to good
industrial and agricultural production. Consecutive good harvests
and increases in produce and farm by-product market prices have
greatly encouraged farmers to grow more to expand the urban
"shopping basket".
</P>
<P>
Rapid increases in the number of overseas businesses and
imports of consumer goods have also helped stabilize the market,
the SSB report says, and about 90 percent of goods are in greater
supply in recent years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970822.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Wants Currency Convertible in W. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian Finance Minister Anthony
Ani Thursday canvassed the convertibility of the national
currency, the Naira, in the west African sub-region to oil the
wheel of cross-border investments.
</P>
<P>
This will eliminate most of the trade barriers in the form of
smuggling and other malpractices, and make Nigeria the center of
west Africa, said the minister quoted by press reports today.
</P>
<P>
Describing the Naira as the "most formidable means of
exchanging in the sub-region," Ani said the currency is virtually
being used in most west African countries including Benin, Niger,
Chad, Cameroun, Ghana, Liberia, Gambia and Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
"In fact, the eco-Naira in these countries can be equated to
Euro-Dollar in Europe," he told members of the Vision 2010
Committee, the country's long-term development planning body, in
the capital Abuja.
</P>
<P>
It is obvious that the ultimate convertibility of the Naira
will play a significant role and will form the best incentive
for Nigerian investors in the sub-region, the minister noted.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the committee should examine the prospects of
realizing the convertibility of the Naira, he added, urging
Nigerians to work towards the goal.
</P>
<P>
The minister also proposed the drawing up of specific
investment protection agreements among members of the Economic
Community of West African States as a way of ensuring the safety
of investments in the sub-region.
</P>
<P>
The agreement will also boost intra-west African trade and
enable Nigerian businessmen to repatriate their capital interest
and dividends "at any time without let or hindrance", he noted.
</P>
<P>
However, the minister warned that such investment should not
result in capital flight, thereby affecting the nation's economy.
</P>
<P>
On the exchange rate of the national currency, he said, the
present administration is striving to make the Naira stronger
through the accumulation of foreign reserves, currently projected
at 7.4 billion U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The current dual exchange rate of the Naira will eventually
give way to one rate, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
