<DOCNO> XIE19970822.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Discovers Previously Unknown Nazi Atrocity Against </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 22 (Xinhua) -- A previously unknown atrocity
committeed by German Nazis against Jews was lately discovered in
France.
</P>
<P>
The daily Dauphine Libere, which is published in Grenoble,
southeast France, said today that 16 Jewish children and
adolescents and two adults were arrested by Gestapos in the late
night of March 23, 1944, in Voiron, the department of Isere in
southeast France.
</P>
<P>
They were deported to Nazi death camps in Auschwitz in Poland,
and Estonia and Lithuania in April and May 1944, and none of them
survived, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The event was recorded in a document which was discovered at
random recently in the archives of a Jewish organization in Paris,
the Israelite Alliance of Paris.
</P>
<P>
Agence France-Presse (AFP) said that the mayor's office of
Voiron had confirmed this report and indicated that the round-up
resulted from a betrayal.
</P>
<P>
The authenticity of the document was also confirmed by experts,
said AFP.
</P>
<P>
The 16 Jewish children and adolescents, aged from seven to 12,
guided by two adults, including the mother of two of the children,
belonged to a French Jewish religious group named "The Association
of Practicing Israelites."
</P>
<P>
This group once sheltered 70 Jewish children, most of them from
Germany and Poland and whose parents were arrested by Gestapos.
</P>
<P>
The members of the group, gathering around a rabbi, took refuge
in the unoccupied zone of southeast France, including Grenoble and
Marseille, as well as Saint-Etienne-de-Crossey which was under
administration of Italy at that time.
</P>
<P>
The mayor's office of Voiron said that the Jews could have
drawn attention from local militiamen who reported to the Germans.
</P>
<P>
A reporter of Dauphine Libere also found two witnesses of the
round-up who kept silent over the atrocity for 53 years until
now. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
