<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Govt Continues Food Supplies to Jaffna </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 22 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan government has
sent 2,692 metric tons of essential food items to the Northern
province by vessel since July in spite of the attempt by Tamil
rebels to disrupt the food supplies to Jaffna peninsula.
</P>
<P>
A press release issued by the Ministry of Defense this
afternoon said another 2,700 MT of foods are being on the way on
board the vessel Lanka Muditha and further 2,200 MT of food items
are being loaded at the Colombo port now.
</P>
<P>
The Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) had attempted to
sabotage passenger services and food supplies to Tamil civilians
in Jaffna peninsula by attacking a few passenger ships and
hijacking another vessel Morang Bong in the first week of July.
</P>
<P>
Efforts were made by the international Committee of the Red
Cross at the request of the government to resume these civilian
and commercial shipping activity, but the LTTE seems determined to
continue with their threats to attack the civilian and commercial
shipping denying the basic needs of nearly half a million people
who live in Jaffna city now, the release added.
</P>
<P>
Jaffna was once the stronghold of the LTTE, who has waged a
guerrilla war for a separate state in the north and east of the
island country since 1983. Government troops recaptured Jaffna
peninsula in May last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970822.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sino-US Project Aims to Make Breakthrough in Petroleum Technology (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 22 (Xinhua) -- A Sino-US technology development
project launched recently promises to benefit the oil industries
of both countries, according to the president of an American
company serving as coordinator of the project.
</P>
<P>
The project aims to develop a device that can map and image the
underground structure of oilfields by way of Cross-Well Electric
Magnetic Imaging (EMI), according to Li Fang, president of
California-based Laurel Industrial Company, Inc.
</P>
<P>
"Doctors use the CT scanner to see the inside of the human
body, and the EMI device, if and when successfully developed, is
the CT scanner of what lies under the ground," says Li Fang, a
Chinese American, in an interview in his Beijing office.
</P>
<P>
The project was initiated by Fang. In 1992, he decided to
bring Chinese and U.S. scientists together for developing the
technology when he got wind that some U.S. scientists in several
prestigious institutions -- University of California at Berkeley,
Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory, Lawrence Livermore National
Laboratory and the Sandia National Laboratory -- were doing
research aimed at developing such a device.
</P>
<P>
Owing to limited research funds, work of the U.S. scientists
had been largely limited to academic research and laboratory
experiments. "With less pressure that what China faces, the
U.S. government and oil industry were investing less than
desirable," Fang said.
</P>
<P>
"China is different. It needs the technology badly," he said.
</P>
<P>
Fang approached China National Petroleum Corp. (CNPC),
suggesting that it finance further research on the U.S. side as
well as field tests of the technology in China, work that is
needed to make the technology a commercial success.
</P>
<P>
A deal was clinched last August when a cooperative agreement
was signed between CNPC's Bureau of Exploration and Fang's Laurel
Industrial Co. representing U.S. researchers. The agreement went
into effect in February, 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970822.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sino-US Project Aims to Make Breakthrough in Petroleum Technology (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
According to the agreement with a term of three years, the
Chinese side will contribute 1.2 million US dollars to further
research and development of the EMI technology and the two sides
will work together on geophysical modeling, system software, field
tests and data interpretation in China's Shengli Oilfield in
eastern Shandong Province with a view to commercializing the
technology. The Chinese and U.S. sides will share research results.
</P>
<P>
"I'm confident of the project's success," Fang says.
</P>
<P>
He noted that, for the oil industry, the biggest issue in the
21st century is not "exploratory" geophysical prospecting aimed at
locating new oil deposits but "development" geophysical
prospecting aimed at pumping more oil from existing fields.
</P>
<P>
Worldwide at present, of all oil deposits that have been
discovered, less than 30 percent are recoverable with present
techniques, and about half of this 30 percent have been pumped
out. How to increase the recovery rate and find "by-passed" oil at
existing fields have been the biggest challenge for the industry.
</P>
<P>
With the device, Fang said, scattered oil pools that have
been "by-passed" during the primary recovery process in existing
oilfields can be detected and geological structure details between
oil wells can be mapped, thereby boosting the rate of recovery.
</P>
<P>
"The outer space is now open to mankind, not so our mother
earth. We hope the device will help geologists and petroleum
engineers see what lies underground," he added.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that the international oil industry, that in
China in particular, badly needs such a device.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970822.0139 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Labor Leader Calls for Reanimation of Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Ehud Barak, the leader of Israel's
opposition Labor Party, said today that an "emergency reanimation"
is needed to relaunch the peace process between Israel and the
Palestinians, while reaffirming his respect for the right of
self-determination by the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with daily Liberation published today, Barak
criticized Israeli Prime Minister Benyamin Netanyahu for failing
to take initiatives with the Palestinians to resume peace talks
after the double bombing attack in Jerusalem late last month.
</P>
<P>
"Don't forget that we are strong, militarily and economically,
and we have the support of the only superpower. We can thus take
initiatives to resolve the conflict," said Barak.
</P>
<P>
He said that what was destroyed since the coming to power of
the conservative government in Israel is the "reciprocal
confidence carefully built by the (former) Labor government."
</P>
<P>
"I don't know whether this crisis of confidence can be
overcome. I hope so, in the interests of the two peoples... But I
don't see either what we could win from a conflict (with
Palestinians)," said Barak.
</P>
<P>
On whether Israel should agree to the establishment of a
Palestinian state, Barak said that it is up to the Palestinians to
determine their final status, as long as they take into
consideration the security of Israel.
</P>
<P>
On the conflict between Israel and Lebanon in southern Lebanon,
Barak said that Israel could withdraw from southern Lebanon stage
by stage if tranquility can be maintained by the Lebanese in that
area.
</P>
<P>
"After a relatively short period of tranquility and
negotiations, we could withdraw from a portion of Lebanese
territory... in four or five phases. After each phase, we will
see if the Lebanese are capable of guarding the situation under
control," he said.
</P>
<P>
As for Israel's dispute with Syria over Golan Heights, he said
that if the Labor Party was in power, it would not stop holding
talks with Damascus to seek an agreement which covers Lebanon,
terrorism, access to water resource, security for the two sides,
normalization of relations and even economic cooperations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
