<DOCNO> XIE19970822.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CBI Fears Strong Pound to Stall UK's Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 22 (Xinhua) -- The Confederation of British
Industry (CBI) predicted a sharp slowdown in the economy next year
after its latest report showed the outlook for exports is the
worst for 14 years.
</P>
<P>
Manufacturers' export orders have slumped to their lowest ebb
for almost five years, according to the latest monthly survey by
the CBI.
</P>
<P>
Concerns that the strong pound could damage growth prospects
for the British economy overshadowed official figures revealing
consumers are spending money faster than at any time since the
third quarter of 1988.
</P>
<P>
City economists argue that the UK's biggest concern is the
rapid growth in consumer spending. During the second quarter,
consumer expenditure rose by 1.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
As consumer spending powers the economy ahead in the short
term, the CBI has cut its forecast next year from 2.7 to 2.5
percent.
</P>
<P>
It is generally believed here that if sterling was 10 percent
higher, the UK's economy might grow by only 2 percent next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
