<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Urges Young Generation's Devotion to Space Cause </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 22 (Xinhua) -- As the fate of the Russia's Mir
space station grabbed the world's attention, President Boris
Yeltsin today called on young Russians to devoted themselves to
the space undertaking.
</P>
<P>
In his weekly radio address, Yeltsin highly praised the
country's achievements in the space and aviation sector and
promised to increase budget allocations for the financially
squeezed industry in 1998.
</P>
<P>
"One should not forget that the status of Russia as a great
power depends to a large extent on the state of our aerospace
industry," Yeltsin said.
</P>
<P>
"I'd like to call on young people to go to work in aircraft
construction firms, in design bureaus. There are new openings,
great prospects," he added.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin's remarks came at a time when Russian cosmonauts were
preparing to make vital repairs to the Mir space station damaged
in an accident last month.
</P>
<P>
The former Soviet Union had made great achievements in space
technology with the credit of sending the first man into space in
1961, and enjoyed a genuine enthusiasm from the public to its
space research plans.
</P>
<P>
But since the breakup of the Soviet Union in 1991, under the
backdrop of a sluggish economy, many Russians have lost interest
and demanded that the expensive space program be dramatically cut.
</P>
<P>
In an upbeat tone, Yeltsin urged Russians to overcome an
indifference to space research, and said he foresaw the time when
space and aviation would once again become the pride of the
nation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
