<HEADLINE> Angolan FM Calls for UN Action to Promote Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Foreign Minister Venancio De
Moura, now on a working visit in Sao Tome and Principe, expressed
his hope Thursday that the U.N. Security Council take up relevant
measures to promote peace process in Angola.
</P>
<P>
According to reports by the Angolan News Agency today, Moura
said, the Security Council should impose timely sanctions on the
rebel National Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA)
which has unilaterally ceased implementation of the Lusaka Peace
Accord signed in 1994.
</P>
<P>
If the council does not show its firm stand on this issue, the
peace process in Angola will be delayed further, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan foreign minister believed that there is full
reason now for the Security Council to impose sanctions on UNITA
so as to avoid further trampling on its resolutions.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan government and people all hope that the Security
Council carry out necessary actions to push forward the precess
of peace and national reconciliation, Moura stressed.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan peace process is currently facing a stalemate. The
UN Security Council will open a special session next Tuesday to
discuss the Angolan peace process. The meeting will pass a
resolution to impose sanctions on UNITA, including limiting UNITA
leaders' visits abroad.
</P>
<P>
However, reports said sanctions measures will not come into
effect immediately to await positive actions from UNITA leaders.
</P>
</TEXT>
