<HEADLINE> Israeli-Egyptian Trade Expected to Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 22 (Xinhua) -- The annual volume of
Israeli-Egyptian trade is expected to rise by 21 percent this year
to reach 100 million U.S. dollars, reported bi-weekly Israel
Business Today.
</P>
<P>
Albert Paposhadu, Chairman of the Israeli-Egyptian Chamber of
Industry and Trade, was quoted as saying the bulk of the increase
will be in agriculture, food products and plants, paper, plastics,
rubber and metal goods.
</P>
<P>
According to Paposhadu, the volume of Israeli exports to Egypt
is set to rise 12 percent to 65 million dollars, while imports
from Egypt will increase 40 percent to 35 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Israeli and Egyptian entrepreneurs have also stepped up their
cooperation by establishing more joint ventures which covered a
range of areas including agriculture, textiles, medical equipment,
air conditioning and refrigeration and plastics.
</P>
<P>
To cope with these developments, the two countries need to
establish joint financial and banking organizations, and insurance
and transportation companies, and the introduction of tax and
custom duties relief, said Paposhadu.
</P>
<P>
He also made a call on Egypt, one of the two Arab countries
that have reached peace with Israel, to support Israel's full
membership of the proposed Arab common market.
</P>
<P>
"Regional economic cooperation which does not include Israel --
which is an integral part of the region -- significantly reduces
its chances of success," said Paposhadu. 
</P>
</TEXT>
