<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Overseas Visitors to Australia Up 5 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Overseas visitors to Australia
in the first seven months of this year numbered 2,456,800, up five
percent compared with the corresponding period in 1996, the
Australian Bureau of Statistics (ABS) said today.
</P>
<P>
Australian Minister in charge of Industry, Science and Tourism
John Moore said the ABS international arrivals data indicated
Australia's 11.8 billion U.S. dollars tourism industry was on
track to meet on official forecast of 7.3 percent growth in 1997.
</P>
<P>
But Tourism Council Australia Managing Director Bruce Baird
said growth from Australia's five key source markets has slowed
with the exception of the United Kingdom and some have slowed
considerably like Japan.
</P>
<P>
The Australian tourism industry must continue to address issues
affecting the market such as the price competitiveness and the
packaging of Australia as a destination, Baird said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
In the seven months to July, Japan accounted for 19 percent of
all visitor arrivals (468,600). New Zealand followed closely with
15 percent and the United Kingdom with nine percent.
</P>
<P>
The number of Japanese tourists, however, was down two percent
on the same period the previous year. Moore attributed the slight
decline in arrivals to uncertainty in the Japanese economy and
strong competition.
</P>
<P>
The survey showed increases for all other top ten countries or
regions, except for Taiwan, which decreased four percent.
</P>
<P>
The largest rise in visitor numbers was recorded from the
Republic of Korea, up 19 percent to 147,300.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia recorded a rise of 17 percent to 108,200, and the
United Kingdom arrivals rose 13 percent to 217,700.
</P>
<P>
The ABS figures show a 13.5 percent decline in permanent
arrivals, compared with June last year. It attributed that to
lower intakes under the migration and humanitarian programs.
</P>
<P>
Permanent arrivals from the Asian region numbered 32,100 in
1996-1997, the past fiscal year ending June 30, 1997, a decline of
10 percent on 1995-1996. Of those about a quarter were born in
China.
</P>
<P>
"Overall in 1996-1997 there were 102,200 permanent and
long-term arrivals from the Asian region and 50,200 permanent and
long-term departures," the ABS said.
</P>
<P>
The report noted 1996-1997 increase in permanent arrivals from
New Zealand (up seven percent to 13,100), South Africa (up one
percent to 3,200) and Taiwan (up 33 percent to 2,200).
</P>
<P>
But in 1996-1997 there were declines in permanent arrivals from
the United Kingdom (down 14 percent to 9,700), China (down 31
percent to 7,800), Bosnia (down 40 percent to 2,100) and Hong Kong
(down eight percent to 3,900).  
</P>
</TEXT>
