<HEADLINE> HK SAR Government to Implement UN Sanctions Regulations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 22 (Xinhua) -- The government of the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) gazetted six regulations
today to give effect to the directives given by the Central
People's Government to the Chief Executive for implementing United
Nations (UN) sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Of the six regulations, two are relating to restrictions on
imports from and exports to Iraq of certain goods and related
financial procedures.
</P>
<P>
Two other regulations are on restrictions on import from and
export to Libya of certain goods as well as on aviation links and
related activities.
</P>
<P>
The remaining two regulations impose arms embargoes against
Somalia, Libya and certain parties in Rwanda and Angola.
</P>
<P>
The Secretary for Trade and Industry of the SAR government,
Denise Yue, explained that the regulations were made under the
enabling provisions of the UN Sanctions Ordinance enacted last
month.
</P>
<P>
"The implementation of UN sanctions is necessary in order to
enable the Central People's Government to meet its international
obligations," Yue said.
</P>
<P>
"It is also necessary to safeguard Hong Kong's reputation as a
responsible trading and financial center and to prevent Hong Kong
from becoming a conduit for those seeking to supply goods,
services and finance to prohibited destinations and persons
connected with them, identified in UN Security Council decisions,"
she added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
