<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Down On Back Of Volatile US Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 22 (Xinhua) -- The Australian sharemarket
closed down today on the back of a volatile New York market which
was expected to fall further overnight, brokers said.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index was down 29.4 points to 2,620.3.
</P>
<P>
When asked what was the reason for the drop, one broker said
"purely New York".
</P>
<P>
"It was expected to be down 20 to 30 points from the opening
bell and realistically that's where it ended up," broker Julian
Reynolds said.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average fell more than 125 points on
Thursday, its fifth straight triple-digit swing, as rising
interest rates derailed the New York stock market's bid at a rapid
recovery from its month's downturn.
</P>
<P>
The four major banks were all down, with ANZ losing 21 cents,
Westpac shedding 14.9 cents, Commonwealth dropping 17 and NAB
slipping 15.3 cents.
</P>
<P>
The gold index was up 5.3 points at 1342.2.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index was down 16.8 points to 1,373.7, while
the all industrials index was down 45.8 points to 4,218.8.
</P>
<P>
Among the resources majors, BHP fell 23 cents, Rio Tinto
dropped 36 cents.
</P>
<P>
Topping volume among the major industrial stocks was Rupert
Murdock's News Corp with a turnover of 7.57 million shares valued
at 43.94 million Australian dollars (32.51 Million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
National turnover totaled 353.64 million shares with a value of
796.45 million Australian dollars (596.54 million US dollars),
with falls of 685 outnumbering rises of 431.  
</P>
