<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Up As Confidence On Rates Grows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 22 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar finished
today stronger against the US currency, driven by growing
confidence that the Reserve Bank of Australia (RBA) won't cut
rates in the near term.
</P>
<P>
The local unit finished at 74.90 US cents, up from 74.44 late
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Overnight, it hit a high in New York of 75.10 US cents, the
first time it has traded through 75 US cents since late June.
</P>
<P>
The push higher in the Australian dollar began on Wednesday,
the day after the RBA released its August bulletin.
</P>
<P>
The central bank's report, interpreted as ruling out further
interest rate cuts in the near term, has set a bulletin tone for
the market which has seen the local unit stronger over the past
three days.
</P>
<P>
"The Australian dollar is looking strong, and it is continuing
the stronger trend," said NatWest strategist Stephen Halmarick.
</P>
<P>
On the cross-rates, the local unit was at 87.72 from 87.79
against the Japanese yen and was at 1.3724 from 1.3815 against the
German mark.  
</P>
