<HEADLINE> Market Distribution Going Strong in China (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 22 (Xinhua) -- China has had some improvements
in its commodity distribution system in the past five years, with
more than 90 percent of its goods sold on the open market and less
than five percent remaining under State control.
</P>
<P>
The central government has loosened price controls for all
consumer goods and gradually freed major farm produce and
by-products like grain and cooking oil from controls, according to
the State Statistics Bureau.
</P>
<P>
Large and medium-sized state commercial enterprises were given
more autonomy in pricing, hiring and income distribution, while
small businesses adopted a state-owned but privately-run
practice. As a result, the state sector has brought about a shift
from central planning to market-oriented operations.
</P>
<P>
A system of different forms of ownership has been taking shape
in the distribution sector over the past five
years. Non-governmental businesses have maintained the fastest
growth, and increased sales from 47 percent in 1992 to more than
70 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Restrictions on overseas-backed enterprises in China's market
has been lifted and six of the world's largest chain-store groups
have opened their outlets in major Chineses cities like Shanghai
and Beijing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
