<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, Malaysia Sign Accord on Joint Venture Paper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 22 (Xinhua) -- China and Malaysia today
signed an agreement on a Sino-Malaysian plantation and pulp paper
mill.
</P>
<P>
Visiting Chinese Premier Li Peng and his Malaysian counterpart
Mahathir Mohammad attended today's signing ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The joint venture project, at an estimated cost of 4.3 billion
ringgit (about 1.6 billion U.S. dollars), represents the single
largest foreign investment by China abroad.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, China and Malaysia will set up two
companies, one for supply of raw materials and the other for a
pulp paper mill. China will have 40 percent of the first company's
share and Malaysia 60 percent, while China shares 60 percent and
Malaysia 40 percent of the second company.
</P>
<P>
The project will have a production capacity of 750,000 metric
tons of pulp and 225,000 metric tons of paper per annum, according
to the agreement.
</P>
<P>
As a substantial portion of the production will be exported to
China, the project will generate foreign exchange earnings and
savings in excess of 1 billion ringgit (about 370 million U.S.
dollars) per annum for Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
To ensure a continuous supply of raw materials for the mill,
the project will have its own sustainable forest management
program, which includes converting and rehabilitating waste and
idle land into productive forest plantation.
</P>
<P>
An estimated 220,000 hectares of forest plantation will be
established with an annual production of 3.8 million cubic meters
of pulpwood to feed the pulp mill.
</P>
<P>
The project, which is expected to create about 6,500 jobs
including 200 managerial and technical positions, will bring about
economic, social and environmental benefits to Malaysia
particularly to the state of Sabah.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed by Chinese Vice Minister in charge of
the State Planning Commission Chen Tonghai, the Lion Group
Chairman Cheng Heng Jem and Sabah State Chief Minister Yong Teck
Lee.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970822.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commonwealth Not to Expel Nigeria : Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 22 (Xinhua) -- The Commonwealth of Nations has
no plan to expel Nigeria from the 52-nation organization,
Secretary-General Emeka Anyaoku said Thursday in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the News Agency of Nigeria, Anyaoku said
though the Commonthwealth summit in October in Edinburgh,
Scotland will deliberate on the Nigerian situation, it will not
wield the big stick ultimately, even if it still finds the
situation unsatisfactory.
</P>
<P>
Anyaoku was in South Africa to consult with President Nelson
Mandela over the coming Commonwealth summit.
</P>
<P>
His comment came amid wild speculations that Nigeria will quit
the Commonthwealth in the fear of being expelled at the summit.
</P>
<P>
When the Commonthwealth suspended Nigeria's membership in 1995
for executing author Ken Saro-Wiwa and eight other minority
activists, it give a two-year ultimatum for Nigeria to improve in
human rights and democracy, before it will be expelled for good.
</P>
<P>
As the ultimatum is drawing near, the fear is that the
Commonwealth might be forced to honour its threat, as dialogue
between the two sides has so far produced no positive results.
</P>
<P>
Another reason behind the speculations is that Nigeria has
been emphasizing its right to find new friends and did new
friendship in non-west countries.
</P>
<P>
On the same day of Anyaoku's comment, Nigerian Foreign
Minister Tom Ikimi announced that Nigeria will open nine new
overseas information centers in Africa, South America and Asia.
</P>
<P>
This move, Ikimi said, is to counter the negative reports of
Nigeria by some sector of the international community and let his
country better known by the outside world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
