<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Party Senior Official Meets Japanese Political Figures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Hu Jintao, a member of the
Standing Committee of the Political Bureau of the Communist Party
of China's Central Committee, meeting today with members of
different political parties from Japan, said that China and Japan
should increase exchanges and strengthen mutual understanding.
</P>
<P>
The group is being led by Wataru Kubo, former general secretary
of the Social Party of Japan (SPJ), and Makoto Tanabe, a former
chairman of the Central Executive Committee and general secretary
of SPJ.
</P>
<P>
Hu said that the two countries should remove obstacles for a
sound and stable development of good neighborly friendship and
that he was very glad to meet them here on the 25th anniversary of
normalization of Sino-Japanese relations.
</P>
<P>
The development of Sino-Japanese friendship oriented to the
21st century is not only in the fundamental interest of the two
peoples but also benefits peace, stability and development of Asia
and the world as a whole, he said.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that abiding by the principles and spirit of the
Sino-Japanese Joint Statement and the Treaty of Peace and
Friendship and having a correct attitude towards problems of the
past and the Taiwan issue are important for the smooth development
of Sino-Japanese relations.
</P>
<P>
Kubo and Tanabe said that they are pleased to visit China again
and see its latest economic developments.
</P>
<P>
They expressed a willingness to continue their work in
developing friendship between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese visitors arrived on Wednesday as guests of the CPC
Central Committee's International Department. They are scheduled
to visit Lanzhou, capital of Gansu Province, and Dunhuang, whose
grottoes are a famous tourist attraction.  
</P>
