<HEADLINE> 76 Killed in Thursday's Fighting in Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 22 (Xinhua) -- More than 60 Tamil rebels were
killed and at least 100 others injured Thursday as government
troops continued their attack on the rebel-held Puliyankulam town
in the Northern province of Sri Lanka, a military spokesman said
today.
</P>
<P>
Ink Dewage, the spokesman, said the troops, supported by armor
and artillery, tried to push forward from a railway station south
of the town, but met strong resistance from the rebels who fired
mortars at the troops.
</P>
<P>
The troops destroyed with artillery fire two vehicles carrying
rebels, and seized a large stock of weapons from the rebels.
</P>
<P>
Dewage said on the troops' side, one officer and 15 soldiers
were killed and two officers as well as 29 soldiers were injured
during Thursday's confrontation.
</P>
<P>
It was the second day the government troops continued their
attack on Puliyankulam, a town near a vital supply route that runs
to the rebel base in Jaffna peninsula.  
</P>
