<HEADLINE> India, Nepal Agree to Discuss Revision of Peace Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 22 (Xinhua) -- India and Nepal have agreed to
discuss specific proposals to revise a bilateral peace and
friendship treaty signed in 1950, the local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached at the end of a two-day talks on
Wednesday and Thursday here between Indian Foreign Secretary
Krishnan Raghunath and his visiting Nepalese counterpart Kumar
Prasad Gyawali.
</P>
<P>
According to a joint press release issued on Thursday night,
the two sides examined various aspects of the treaty in the
context of suggestions for a review by Nepal, particularly the
security-related clauses concerning the ways and sources for Nepal
to import sophisticated arms.
</P>
<P>
Both sides also discussed border and economic cooperation
issues, the release said, adding that the talks were held in a
friendly, frank and cordial atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
The release said that discussions would be continued at the
next round of foreign secretary level talks this year on mutually
convenient dates.  
</P>
</TEXT>
