<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 22 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from the Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Bahrain's foreign trade deficit rose to some 264.7
million U.S. dollars in the first quarter of 1997, up from 259.4
million dollars in the same period of 1996, according to official
statistics reaching here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Bahrain exported goods worth 339.8 million dollars in the
first quarter of 1997 and imported goods worth 604.5 million
dollars, said the statistics issued by Bahrain's Central
Statistics Organization.
</P>
<P>
Bahrain's main exports are oil, gas and aluminum.
</P>
<P>
Bahrain's major markets include the United Kingdom, India,
Japan and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Oman's oil exports rose 5.5 percent to 101.279
million barrels in the first four months of 1997, compared with 96
million barrels in the same period in 1996, a local newspaper said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Japan topped the list of importing countries of Oman's oil in
the first quarter of this year, taking 28.4 million barrels, down
from 31.1 million barrels in the same period in 1996, Gulf News
quoted a monthly statistical bulletin issued by Oman's ministry of
development as saying.
</P>
<P>
China was the second biggest importer in this period, doubling
its imports from Oman to 27.135 million barrels from 13.146
million in the same period in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's imports in this period stood at 20.793 million
barrels, followed by Korea with 16.292 million.
</P>
<P>
SANAA -- The Yemeni government would raise the prices of fuel,
electricity and basic commodities in September, as part of the
third phase of the economic reform program adopted by Yemen since
the beginning of 1995, officials said.
</P>
<P>
Thursday's "Al Thawra" newspaper quoted unnamed sources in the
ministry of petroleum as saying that next month will witness a
rise in the prices of petroleum and its by-products.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, government sources say that the prices of the basic
commodities will be relatively higher over the coming days, as
part of the new measures to reform the country's economic
structure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
