<HEADLINE> Surrendered Rebel Commander Discovers Armory in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 22 (Xinhua) -- A former rebel commander, who
lost his confidence in fighting against the government, has
discovered an armory for the government, "The Monitor" reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Oyet Pen Mogi Lakweka, a former commander of the Lord's
Resistance Army (LRA), told a press conference Wednesday in
northern Gulu district that he saw no reason to fight the
government any more.
</P>
<P>
He helped the government troops find 53 sub-machine guns, five
light machine guns, a motor, three grenades, 210 loose
ammunitions and four anti-personnel mines in Kilak hill in the
district, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
There are more underground arms and ammunitions in the north
to be found, Lakweka said.
</P>
<P>
Shaban Bantariza, Public Relation Officer of the fourth
division, said the acquisition of the weapons helped a lot in
destroying the LRA leadership.
</P>
<P>
What Lakweka did seems to be one of the greatest loss the
LRA ever suffered in its history, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The government troops will receive the former rebels if they
wished to join them, said the paper quoting Shaban Bantariza.
</P>
<P>
LRA is a rebel group operating in the north and has bases in
southern Sudan. It had thousands of members in the past and now
has some three hundred fighters, an early report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
