<DOCNO> XIE19970822.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Modernization In Tibet (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Taxicabs carry passengers to
luxury hotels that line Lhasa's streets, and MD-82 passenger jets
land and take off at the "roof of the world", all part of Tibet's
global modernization enthusiasm, which has shocked the rest of
China since the late 1970s.
</P>
<P>
Some 62 big projects are under construction in the Tibet
Autonomous Region to open iron mines, thermal-energy plants,
highways, and satellite ground stations.
</P>
<P>
Scholars at the ongoing Beijing Seminar on Tibetan Studies now
maintain that the modernization of Tibet is not a mere change of
the appearance of cities and villages.
</P>
<P>
"Tibetans' incomes have increased, and so has their life
expectancy. And they have more dynamic thoughts on their minds,"
says Li Tao, a researcher whose recent study shows that more
Tibetan farmers are interested in doing business and traveling to
big cities and other provinces because they have more money and
want to make more money.
</P>
<P>
Tibet's economy has been growing at 10 percent annually for
past three consecutive years. In the first half of 1997, more than
100,000 tourists visited Tibet, bringing cash to the region, and
perhaps more important, information. Tibetans now have web sites
of their own and communicate on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
Scholars agree that Tibet is casting off its image as a
conservative and isolated land, becoming more open, and they say
that change is important for the region, which was still a society
of serfs half a century ago.
</P>
<P>
"Not long ago, Tibetan farmers would throw chemical fertilizers
into rivers, because gods and nature were the only things they
worshipped. Now, what they care about most is how to get enough
chemical fertilizer to increase their crop output," Li Tao says.
</P>
<P>
At least 80,000 words about modern science and technology,
including the now fashionable word 'clone', have found their way
into the Tibetan language. "We believe that even the oldest and
the most exquisite language must continue to evolve in keeping
with the times," said Hu Tan, of the Tibetan Studies Center.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970822.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Modernization In Tibet (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
According to Nancy Levine, a professor studying Tibetan
households at the University of California, Tibetans used to
worked 30 days a month, but now have more free time.
</P>
<P>
Last year, half of the Tibetans took part in grass-roots
elections to chose deputies to the local People's Congress.
</P>
<P>
Religion, which is vital to Tibetans, is changing gradually. In
the old days, if a Tibetan was sick, the only thing to do was to
burn incense and pray in front of gods, but now he or she will
go to a hospital.
</P>
<P>
More local people have got used to the existence of
hydro-electric power plants built on lakes which are the homes of
gods according to Tibetan mythology.
</P>
<P>
However, their pious adherence to Buddhism is almost
unchanged. The difference is that they enjoy more religious
freedoms than before and can go to monasteries if they wish,
according to Elaine Robson, a British scholar who has visited
Tibet four times.
</P>
<P>
Lawrence Epstein, a professor at University of Washington, says
that the process of commercializing ethnic culture has largely
reshaped local ways of life. However, it has also enhanced local
self-awareness of Tibetan culture.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, some Chinese scholars are not entirely satisfied
with the degree of modernization. Yu Changjiang of Beijing
University found that the use of machines in rural areas has
helped peasants save time. But, the problem is that many of them
find they have nothing to do in the free time provided by the
machine.
</P>
<P>
Ma Rong, a social-anthropology researcher, explains that this
can be attributed to a higher rate of illiteracy in Tibet, a
comparative lack of modern scientific knowledge, and a shortage of
sources of entertainment.
</P>
<P>
This shows that the modernization drive in Tibet should be
increased, Li Tao said. "Some people wish to preserve a primitive
and isolated Tibet as a sample world where they can visit for
novelty. This is a very irresponsible attitude," she added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
