<DOCNO> XIE19970822.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mugabe Pledges to Consider War Veterans' Demands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert
Mugabe has promised to come up demands of the war veterans at the
cabinet meeting next Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The president made the promise after a nine-hour meeting
Thursday with leadership of the war veterans during the country's
liberation struggle. At the end of the meeting, war veterans
leader Chenjerai Hunzvi said that they were happy with the
outcome of the marathon meeting which did not even break for
lunch or refreshments, reported the Zimbabwe News Agency today.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe had undertaken that next Wednesday he will give
feedback to the War Veterans Association on the decision due to
be made by cabinet, Hunzvi said.
</P>
<P>
"We could not be happy and we could not be smiling," said
Hunzvi, chairman of the association when asked if Mugabe had
accepted their demands.
</P>
<P>
Among the demands are that each war veteran should receive a
gratuity of 500,000 Zimbabwe Dollars (43,000 U.S. Dollars) and a
monthly pension of 2,000 Zimbabwe Dollars (174 U.S. Dollars).
</P>
<P>
The war veterans also demand that 50 percent of all
ex-combatants needing settlement should be given land by December
this year and the rest by July next year.
</P>
<P>
The ex-combatants want to go into the war of economic
emancipation of the black majority and hence their desire to
participate in agricultural production and other industrial and
commercial activities, Hunzvi added.
</P>
<P>
He said they were happy the meeting had agreed to the
principle of affirmative action for ex-combatants in the
allocation of high ranking positions in the diplomatic service
and other organs of the government.
</P>
<P>
The meeting at Mugabe's official residence came after hundreds
of ex-combatants resorted to picketing ruling Zimbabwe African
National Union-Patriotic Front (ZANU-PF) and government offices,
demanding disbursement of disability pensions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
