<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970822.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Grave Development Harmful to Sino-Japanese Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 22 (Xinhua) -- A commentary entitled "A Grave
Development Harmful to Sino-Japanese Relations," carried in
today's People's Daily, rebutted some Japanese officials for their
remarks that violate China's sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
The commentary said, on August 17, Japanese Chief Cabinet
Secretary Seiroku Kajiyama remarked that new Japan-U.S. defense
cooperation guidelines would cover the Taiwan Straits.
</P>
<P>
This violated China's sovereignty and met opposition from the
ruling Social Democratic Party (SDP) and the New Party Sakigake
(NPS). At a tripartite meeting reviewing the guidelines two days
later, the SDP accused Kajiyama of creating chaos and restated
that the Taiwan Straits are outside the areas covered by the
guidelines. Agreeing with SDP, the NPS pointed out that when
defining the "defense areas," the Taiwan Straits should not be
included.
</P>
<P>
However, Japanese Deputy Foreign Minister Shunji Yanai,
"confirmed" Kajiyama's remarks on August 18, saying that, from the
united view of the Japanese government since 1960, Taiwan is
within the "Far East" region defined by the Japan-U.S. security
treaty.
</P>
<P>
One day later, on August 19, Foreign Minister Yukihiko Ikeda
again openly claimed that Kajiyama's remarks were made in line
with the consistent position of the Japanese government.
</P>
<P>
On August 20, Japan's Deputy Chief Cabinet Secretary Kaoru
Yosano came forward and said Kajiyama's remarks did not contradict
the government's stance, and even hoped to get "understanding"
from the Chinese government.
</P>
<P>
Such remarks by senior Japanese officials involve a major
question of principle in Sino-Japanese relations, that is, how to
look at the 1972 Sino-Japanese Joint Statement and the 1978
Sino-Japanese treaty of peace and friendship, which laid the
foundation of Sino-Japanese bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
It is known to all that at the time when the Japan-U.S.
security treaty was revised in 1960, it was Nobusuke Kishi's
government, which had always been hostile to China and maintained
the so-called diplomatic relations with Taiwan, that was ruling
Japan.
</P>
<P>
In 1972, Japan "severed its relations" with Taiwan and
recognized the government of the People's Republic of China as the
sole legal government of China. Only under such circumstances, did
China and Japan normalize their relations.
</P>
<P>
China and Japan noted in the 1972 joint statement that the
government of the People's Republic of China reaffirms that Taiwan
is an inalienable part of the territory of the People's Republic
of China. The government of Japan fully understands and respects
this stand of the government of China and adheres to its stand of
complying with Article 8 of the Potsdam Proclamation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
