<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Grave Development Harmful to Sino-Japanese Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In 1978, the two countries signed the Treaty of Peace and
Friendship, confirming that the joint statement constitutes the
basis of the relations of peace and friendship between the two
countries and that the principles enunciated in the joint
statement should be strictly observed. Both article 1 and article
3 in the treaty reiterate the principle of non-interference in
each other's internal affairs. These are solemn promises the
Japanese government has made to the whole world.
</P>
<P>
But, Kajiyama and his like, stubbornly sticking to the
anti-China stand of the Kishi government, wanted to include the
Taiwan Straits in the joint U.S.-Japanese defense areas. This
constitutes nothing but an open interference in China's internal
affairs and gross violation of the two basic documents on the
Sino-Japanese relations.
</P>
<P>
People cannot help but ask how after all these Japanese
government officials evaluate the current Sino-Japanese
relations? And where do they intend to lead the relations to?
</P>
<P>
As a matter of fact, following the normalization of relations
between China and Japan, chief Japanese cabinet members clearly
stated Japan's stand on the issue of "defense areas."
</P>
<P>
For instance, on November 11, 1972, Minister of Foreign Affairs
Masayoshi Ohira, one of the signers of the join statement, pointed
out in parliamentary debates that clauses on Taiwan contained in
the 1969 Japan-U.S. joint statement reflected only views of the
Japanese and American leaders on the situation in Taiwan at that
time.
</P>
<P>
He said, the Taiwan issue is "China's internal affair" and
Japan should take a cautious attitude toward it for the sake of
the friendly relations between China and Japan.
</P>
<P>
On December 12, 1978, Japanese Foreign Minister Sunao Sonoda,
plenipotentiary to the signing of the Sino-Japanese treaty, told
the parliamentary hearing that with the normalization of
Sino-Japan relations, Article 6 concerning the Far East of the
Japan-U.S. security treaty concerning the Far East had become
invalid.
</P>
<P>
However, today, some Japanese officials claimed that Japan has
never changed its stand of 1960. This kind of quibble regardless
of historical facts is evidently intended to seek excuses for the
political pursuit of some politicians, the commentary noted.
</P>
<P>
The maintenance and development of friendly relations between
China and Japan conform to the fundamental interests of the two
nations, the commentary stressed.
</P>
<P>
What deserves vigilance is that there are always people in
Japan who want to drag the Sino-Japanese relations backward.
</P>
<P>
Today, they do not balk at fostering the grave development in
the Sino-Japanese relations by expressing light opinions about
such a sensitive issue as the inclusion of the Taiwan Straits in
Japan's "defense areas." They are trying to back the car of
history and their act goes against the common wishes of the
Chinese and Japanese people, concluded the commentary. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
