<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Wool Prices Down by 2 Percent on Average </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 22 (Xinhua) -- A weaker than expected market
had seen wool auction prices fall by 2 percent on average at sales
in Sydney and Melbourne this week, the Australian Council of Wool
Exporters (ACWE) said today.
</P>
<P>
The Wool Index eastern market indicator dropped by 14
Australian cents (10.3 U.S. cents) to finish at 689 Australian
cents (509 U.S. cents) a kilogram clean.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Wool Exchange (AWEX) northern and southern
regional price indicators closed at 765 and 716 Australian cents
(about 566 and 529 U.S. cents) a kilogram clean, down 13
Australian cents (9.6 U.S. cents) and nine cents (6.6 U.S. cents)
respectively for the week.
</P>
<P>
The AWEX national index fell by nine points to finish at 987
with the northern and southern indices falling by 17 and 12 points
to end the week at 1,003 and 966 points respectively.
</P>
<P>
A total of 76,029 bales were offered with a pass in rate of
15.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
"With it being a traditionally quiet period for European
interests, it is thought that Chinese customers might by testing
out the underlying strength in the market at the present time,"
ACWE said.
</P>
<P>
It said most downstream processors were expected to be
comfortable with a Wool Index eastern indicator of around 700
Australian cents (518 U.S. cents) a kilogram clean, but ACWE
warned the relatively high price of wool against other fiber was a
continuing cause for concern.
</P>
<P>
More than 64,000 bales have been registered for sale in
Newcastle near Sydney and Fremantle near Perth next week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
