<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Construction of Cobalt Plant Starts in Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 22 (Xinhua) -- The construction of a 110
million U.S. Dollar cobalt plant has started in Kasese,
southwestern uganda, reported the local daily "The Monitor"
today.
</P>
<P>
The Kasese Cobalt Company directors were quoted as saying the
construction work will be completed in about months.
</P>
<P>
The directors who met Ugandan President Y. Museveni in the
president's home village near Mbarara town on Wednesday said the
plant will be commissioned during the last quarter of 1998 and
commercial production is expected to begin in the first quarter
of 1999.
</P>
<P>
At its full capacity, the plant will produce 1,000 metric tons
of pure cobalt metal per annum, earning the country over 40
million dollars annually and will be ranked 5th among the world
cobalt producers.
</P>
<P>
This means cobalt will be the second to coffee as one of the
country's most important foreign exchange earners.
</P>
<P>
The project is composed of cobalt processing plant, a 10
megawatt hydro-power scheme and limestone quarry.
</P>
<P>
The plant, called the Kasese Cobalt Company Ltd., is a joint
venture, with Kilembe Mines Ltd. occupying 45 percent shares and,
Banff Resources Ltd. and Banffa Canadian Firm altogether having
55 percent shares.
</P>
<P>
The plant will initially depend on a huge stockpile of cobalt
pyrites left behind in the 1960s during copper mining at Kilembe,
Kasese.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian company has been in Uganda for two years on
exploratory work.
</P>
<P>
Cobalt is used in construction of aircraft among other uses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970822.0209 </DOCNO>
