<DOCNO> XIE19970822.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Sees 23.4 Billion Dollars in Outstanding Obligations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Bank of Thailand, the central
bank, Thursday announced that Thailand has commitments totaling
23.4 billion U.S. dollars in outstanding currency forward
obligations over the next 12 months, triggering a surprise on the
financial markets, a local newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
Of these obligations, 14.8 billion dollars was for off-shore
contracts and the remaining was for on-shore activities to boost
the baht, The Nation said.
</P>
<P>
The figures were revealed for the first time Thursday as the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) approved a bail-out deal to
support Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper pointed out that the announcement suggests that
Thailand's move in defending the baht in mid-May this year has
significantly run down its foreign exchange reserves.
</P>
<P>
The Thai central bank said that Thailand's foreign exchange
reserves stood at 32.4 billion dollars at the end of June, but
analysts warned against any attempt to deduct the 23.4 billion
dollars in forward obligations from the June reserves of 32.4
billion dollars, according to the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Some of the forward contracts may have already matured as
delivery obligations of those foreign exchange swaps made earlier
by the Thai central bank to defend the baht set at a certain date
in the future, they added.
</P>
<P>
Thai central bank governor Chaiyawat Wibulsawasdi said that the
outstanding forward obligations had been taken into account during
consultations with the IMF in preparation of the bail-out package
for Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Since the forward obligations will be effective over the next
12 months, it may run down over Thailand's foreign reserves, but
not immediately, he said.
</P>
<P>
Some forward obligations may be rolled over, he added.
</P>
<P>
Chaiyawat also noted that the 8.6 billion dollars for on-shore
transactions is an instrument of domestic liquidity management and
a part of monetary policy operation.
</P>
<P>
This is normally rolled over and will not seriously affect
Thailand's foreign reserves position, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
