<HEADLINE> Panama Announces New Investments in Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The Panamanian government
will invest 180 million U.S. dollars in new education projects in
the next seven years, Panamanian President Ernesto Perez
Balladares announced today.
</P>
<P>
The investment excludes current spending allocated annually in
the government budget for the payment of teachers, school
maintenance and administrative spending, said the president.
</P>
<P>
Of these funds, 73 million dollars will be invested in a "more
ambitious" projects such as reforms to the curricula and training
of teachers, and academic and administrative personnel.
</P>
<P>
Another 58 million dollars will be directed at the construction
of 2,000 new classrooms and the improvement of basic education for
about 180,000 students of the poorest communities of the country,
added Perez.
</P>
<P>
The rest of the investment will be channelled into equipment
and tools for the professional and technical education centers,
and help for the modernization of the Pro-Library Foundation,
Balladares said. 
