<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Sri Lanka's Economic Performance in First </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's economic activity
has recovered during the first half of this year from the
depressed conditions in 1996.
</P>
<P>
As against a growth rate of 3.8 percent in 1996, all major
sectors performed well in the first six months of this year and a
growth rate of around 6 percent is expected in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Significant economic performance was recorded in production.
Agricultural production improved with more favorable weather
conditions than last year.
</P>
<P>
Tea output has recovered completely with very attractive
prices. Rubber production increased 4 percent but prices declined
12 percent. Coconut production increased 2 percent and the paddy
harvest was higher by 9.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Other agricultural products also performed well and exports
increased 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
In the industrial sector, output showed a possible growth of 10
to 12 percent while the value of industrial exports increased 22
percent in the first half of 1997.
</P>
<P>
All industrial exports except petroleum products increased
considerably with garments and textiles up 25 percent during this
period.
</P>
<P>
In the electricity sector, power generation capacity increased
8 percent in the first half of 1997.
</P>
<P>
With the growth of exports and imports and the expansion in the
transshipment cargo handled, port services became a major
contributor to the national output. Total cargo handled at the
ports increased 24 percent.
</P>
<P>
The telecommunication facilities have been expanding and will
be a key contributor to overall economic expansion.
</P>
<P>
Tourist arrivals increased 21 percent to over 174,200 during
the first half of 1997 and tourism earnings increased 33 percent.
</P>
<P>
Consumer price hike dropped to 13.9 percent in July 1997 from
15.9 percent in December 1996. The main reason for this change was
the decline in the rate of growth of money supply and the
improvement in the growth of domestic supply of food commodities.
</P>
<P>
Major changes were made in the monetary policy during the first
half of this year. A new foreign currency loan scheme through
domestic units of the banks was introduced.
</P>
<P>
The balance of payments also reflected the improved performance
of the economy. Total exports in Special Drawing Rights (SDR)
terms increased 18 percent in the first six months and total
imports grew 22 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Colombo Stock Exchange activities made gains considerably
this year, reflecting improved investor confidence in the economy
and economic policies of the country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970822.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
