<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand to Improve Disclosure of Economic Data </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 22 (Xinhua) -- The Thai government will take
steps to improve its publication and dissemination of key economic
data to keep the public well-informed of the country's economic
development.
</P>
<P>
This commitment is stated in a statement released Thursday by
the Bank of Thailand after the International Monetary Fund (IMF)
approved a standby credit of 4 billion U.S. dollars as part of the
international rescue package for Thailand in Washington the same
day.
</P>
<P>
Under the commitment, the Thai central bank will begin on
August 29 to publish fortnightly data on key elements of its
assets and liabilities, including the country's gross
international reserves.
</P>
<P>
The Thai central bank and Finance Ministry also will coordinate
closely with financial institutions to ensure the timely
dissemination of information on the financial position, including
non-performing loans and capital adequacy, of financial
institutions.
</P>
<P>
In addition, in order to increase transparency and efficiency
of data dissemination to the public, the government will
strengthen observance of data dissemination in line with the IMF's
special data dissemination standards and seek related technical
assistance from the IMF.  
</P>
</TEXT>
