<DOCNO> XIE19970822.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Government Passes 1998 Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The Russian government today
passed the 1998 budget presented by Finance Ministry at a meeting
presidented over by Prime Minister, Viktor Chernomyrdin.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, the Economic Ministry forecast the GDP next
year will increase by two percent, industrial output value will go
up by two to three percent and agricultural output value by three
percent of increase. Investment in capital construction would rise
by two percent. This is the most optimistic expectation during the
recent seven years.
</P>
<P>
The principle for budget next year is living within its mean
instead of keeping need within limits of income before. The total
of expenditure next year will amount to 472 billion new ruble
(about 81.3 million U.S. dollars), in which, state managing
spending is 11.4 billion new ruble (about 1.965 million dollars),
defense expenditure is 94.5 billion new ruble (about 1.629 million
dollars), budget in science and technology is 13.4 billion new
ruble (about 2.303 million dollars), and outlay on education is
16.3 billion new ruble (about 2.9 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
The budget deficit is expected to total 132 billion new ruble
(about 22.7 million dollars), accounting for the 0.42 percent of
the GDP, in which, 102 billion (about 17.6 million dollars) will
be made up by borrowing internal debt, the figure of recent
foreign debt has reached 9.6 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that the total foreign debt will rise to 140.8
billion dollars by January 1, 1999, and the inflation rate next
year will fall to 0.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin summed up at the meeting that cutting down income
and spending and defaulting allocation will be removed next
year. He said that stable political situation is conducive to the
implement of the budget. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970822.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Li Peng Outlines Principles on Sino-ASEAN Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Chinese Premier Li
Peng today outlined five principles on strengthening future
cooperation between China and the ASEAN countries.
</P>
<P>
In a speech at the Institute of Diplomatic and Foreign
Relations, Li said, "We are ready to join ASEAN countries to work
unremittingly for good-neighborly and friendly relations geared to
the 21st century."
</P>
<P>
To this end, Li proposed the following five principles:
</P>
<P>
-- Respecting each other and treating each other as equals.
</P>
<P>
Li said China has always maintained that each and every country
in the world has the right to choose its own political structure
or development path in light of its national conditions and that
Other countries are not allowed to interfere in whatever way.
</P>
<P>
He said, "In our view, all countries, big or small, strong or
weak, rich or poor, are equal members of the international
community and are entitled to participate in regional and
international affairs on an equal footing. Such rights should be
fully respected."
</P>
<P>
-- Strengthening dialogue and intensifying consultation.
</P>
<P>
The full dialogue partership established between China and
ASEAN represents an important channel for us to have closer
dialogue and consultation, the Chinese premier said.
</P>
<P>
"We should further increase exchanges between leaders as well
as between people of various circles for broad exchanges of views
on issues of common concern with a view to increasing mutual
understanding and broadening consensus, " Li said.
</P>
<P>
-- Seeking common development based on mutual benefit.
</P>
<P>
Li said, "As the economic factor rises in importance in
international relations, economic cooperation has become a major
underpin for the development of state-to-state relations."
</P>
<P>
China and ASEAN countries have their respective strong
points. These advantages in such fields as natural resources,
technological know-how, capital and market can be brought to
complement one another, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The potential for our economic cooperation is indeed enormous,
areas broad and prospects highly promising. We can very well draw
on each other's rich experience in economic development to make up
for our own deficiencies in the interest of achieving common
development, " he added.
</P>
<P>
-- Supporting each other and expanding cooperation. "We should
step up our mutual assistance and coordination at the UN, APEC,
ASEM and ARF in order to safeguard the shared rights and interests
of the developing countries, " Li said.
</P>
<P>
-- Bearing in mind the larger picture, seeking common ground
while putting aside differences.
</P>
<P>
"While we share broad common interests in the development of
state-to-state relations, it is hardly avoidable that certain
disputes or differences will come up, " Li said, " Efforts should
be made to seek a gradual solution to the problems with a
forward-looking approach through friendly consultations on an
equal footing."
</P>
<P>
"As for differences and disputes that can not be resolved for
the time being, they can be approached in the spirit of seeking
common ground while shelving differences instead of being allowed
to hinder the development of normal relations, " he said.
</P>
<P>
China has noted with pleasure that ASEAN, as an important
regional organization, is playing an increasingly important role
in maintaining regional peace and promoting economic development,
the Chinese premier said.
</P>
<P>
"China stands ready to continue its productive cooperation with
ASEAN countries," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970822.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier Gives Speech in Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Chinese Premier Li
Peng today delivered a speech at a welcoming meeting hosted by the
Institute of Diplomatic and Foreign Relations of Malaysia,
elaborating on China's stand on the good-neighborly relations
oriented toward the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
The following is the full text of the speech entitled "Toward a
Relationship of Friendship and Good-Neighborliness Geared to the
21st Century."
</P>
<P>
At the invitation of Prime Minister Datuk Seri Dr. Mahathir, I
have come to this country for an official good-will visit. It
gives me great pleasure today to have the opportunity to meet with
all of you here and deliver a speech at the welcoming meeting
hosted by the famous Institute of Diplomatic and Foreign
Relations. I would also like to take this opportunity to express
my heartfelt thanks and cordial greetings to the host, the
Hon. Dato's Abdullah bin Ahmad Badawi, Minister of Foreign Affairs
and all the guests present.
</P>
<P>
Now, I would like to brief you on China's economic development
and also make a few observations on the further development of
amicable cooperation between China and ASEAN countries.
</P>
<P>
Beginning in the late 1970s, China entered a new historical
period of reform, opening-up and modernization. Over the past 19
years, China has all along kept a good momentum of economic growth
and the quality of people's life has improved
noticeably. Breakthroughs have been made in our economic
restructuring aimed at establishing a socialist market economy and
the pattern of opening-up has basically taken shape. In recent
years, as a result of strengthened macro economic control by the
government, we have brought under control inflation which was once
quite serious and ushered in a favorable situation characterized
by high growth rate, low price hikes and smooth and coordinated
growth of the national economy.
</P>
<P>
We in China have formulated development plans for the last five
years of this century and on longer-range objectives to the year
2010. Implementation of these plans in the past two years has been
quite good. Our objective is, through the two switches in economic
system and mode of economic growth, to carry out the strategies of
revitalization through science and technology and of sustainable
development and to unswervingly implement the policy of opening-up
with a view to realizing economic development and all-round social
progress. China will keep its economic growth rate at over 8
percent in the last five years of this century and over 7 percent
in the first ten years of the next century. The aggregate national
strength will be further enhanced and people's living standards
improved more substantially. Compared with the past, our progress
has been tremendous. Yet we are quite clear that as we press
ahead, there are still many difficulties, especially given the
fact that China has a large population and weak economic
foundation. China is still at a rather low level in per capita
terms even compared with certain developing countries in Asia. We
need to work very hard for several more decades in order to
realize modernization and attain the level of averagely developed
countries. We are confident that guided by the theory of building
socialism with Chinese characteristics initiated by Deng Xiaoping,
we are bound to attain the goal of modernization in China.
</P>
<P>
China and Southeast Asian nations had similar past of prolonged
foreign aggression, and they are now both faced with a common task
of developing the national economy. Moreover, they share the need
for securing regional and international peace. We are ready to
join ASEAN countries to work unremittingly for good-neighborly and
friendly relations geared to the 21st century. To this end, we
would like to propose the following:
</P>
<P>
-- Respecting each other and treating each other as equals. We
have always maintained that each and every country in the world
has the right to choose its own political structure or development
path in light of its national conditions. Other countries are not
allowed to interfere in whatever way. In our view, all countries,
big or small, strong or weak, rich or poor, are equal members of
the international community and are entitled to participate in
regional and international affairs on an equal footing. Such
rights should be fully respected.
</P>
<P>
-- Strengthening dialogue and intensifying consultation. The
full dialogue partership established between China and ASEAN
represents an important channel for us to have closer dialogue and
consultation. We should further increase exchanges between leaders
as well as between people of various circles for broad exchanges
of views on issues of common concern with a view to increasing
mutual understanding and broadening consensus.
</P>
<P>
-- Seeking common development based on mutual benefit. As the
economic factor rises in importance in international relations,
economic cooperation has become a major underpin for the
development of state-to-state relations. China and ASEAN countries
have their respective strong points. These advantages in such
fields as natural resources, technological know-how, capital and
market can be brought to complement one another. The potential for
our economic cooperation is indeed enormous, areas broad and
prospects highly promising. We can very well draw on each other's
rich experience in economic development to make up for our own
deficiencies in the interest of achieving common development.
</P>
<P>
-- Supporting each other and expanding cooperation. We should
step up our mutual assistance and coordination at the UN, APEC,
ASEM and ARF in order to safeguard the shared rights and interests
of the developing countries.
</P>
<P>
-- Bearing in mind the larger picture, seeking common ground
while putting aside differences. While we share broad common
interests in the development of state-to-state relations, it is
hardly avoidable that certain disputes or differences will come
up. Efforts should be made to seek a gradual solution to the
problems with a forward-looking approach through friendly
consultations on an equal footing. As for differences and disputes
that can not be resolved for the time being, they can be
approached in the spirit of seeking common ground while shelving
differences instead of being allowed to hinder the development of
normal relations.
</P>
<P>
In the 50s and 60s, the historical trend towards national
independence and liberation was irreversible. Today, the trend
towards multi-polarization is accelerating and it has again become
an irreversible historical trend to strive for world peace,
national development and social progress. We have noted with
pleasure that ASEAN, as an important regional organization, is
playing an increasingly important role in maintaining regional
peace and promoting economic development. China stands ready to
continue its productive cooperation with ASEAN countries.
</P>
<P>
At the end of this year, the leaders of East Asian countries
will have an informal summit in Kuala Lumpur. President Jiang
Zemin of China will, upon invitation, participate in this
distinguished gathering, which will be a major event in the
history of China-ASEAN relations. Let us join hands in a concerted
effort to promote the establishment of a fair and just new
international political and economic order characterized by peace
and stability. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970822.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
