<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peru Buys Back $3.494 Billion in Foreign Debt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The Peruvian government has paid
back 3.494 billion U.S. dollars in foreign debt, Economy and
Finance Minister Jorge Camet says.
</P>
<P>
Of the total, 1.745 billion dollars pays back part of the
principal, and the rest covers interest, Camet told the Congress.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the general debt strategy and the buying back
program, the country's long-term and medium-term public debts had
reduced from 19.327 billion dollars to 18.585 billion dollars, the
minister said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the country's hard currency reserves reached 10
billion dollars as of August 19.
</P>
<P>
The debt-buying back operation was started in 1994 with
resources from the Bank of the Nation. It represented a
disbursement of 906 million dollars, said the minister. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
