<HEADLINE> U.S. Ambassador Rules out All-out Lebanese-Israeli </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. ambassador to Lebanon
said here today that all-out fighting between Lebanon and Israel
will not take place, and what happens now is just tit-for-tat
attacks between Hezbollah guerrillas and Israel.
</P>
<P>
After meeting with Lebanese Parliament Speaker Nabih Berri,
Ambassador Richard Jones told reporters that he does not believe
the both sides are seeking to escalate the tension, Lebanese
Central News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Asked if the U.S. could guarantee that Israel will not strike
Lebanese vital installations, Jones said he is not in the position
to make any promises.
</P>
<P>
However, he said the efforts made by the U.S. before are
fruitful.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the role of the five-nation cease-fire monitoring
committee, brokered by the U.S. after Israel's 16-day blitz of
Lebanon in April last year, Jones said that the establishment of
the committee is for reducing the escalation of fighting, not
controlling the situation.
</P>
<P>
He said the committee has made contributions on this issue.
</P>
<P>
The monitoring committee made up of Lebanese, Israeli, Syrian,
US and French officials is holding a meeting in the Lebanese
southern town of Naquar, near the Israeli border, to discuss
complaints by Lebanon and Israel of truce violations.
</P>
<P>
Israeli warplanes Wednesday raided at least three areas in
Lebanon in a bid to warn the Lebanese government to curb
Hezbollah's military activity against Israel.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli air raid was apparently a reaction to the Katyusha
rockets fired by Hezbollah Tuesday at northern Israeli panhandle
of Galilee, causing two injuries and some damage.
</P>
<P>
The Hezbollah's attack was a response to the shelling Monday by
the South Lebanese Army, Israeli militia ally, on Lebanese port
city of Saida which killed nine people and wounded 43
people. 
</P>
