<HEADLINE> Israel Denounces PNA Dialogue with Opposition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Israel today strongly
denounced the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) for conducting
dialogue with militant opposition groups.
</P>
<P>
In the West Bank city of Ramallah, PNA President Yasser Arafat
hosted the second session of the "national unity conference" with
senior leaders from Palestinian opposition groups led by the
Islamic Resistance Movement (Hamas) and Islamic Jihad.
</P>
<P>
The conference was held by the PNA in an attempt to mobilize
all forces to fight Israeli siege and sanctions against the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
This was a follow-up to the first meeting held in Gaza
Wednesday, during which Arafat not only hugged and embraced
Hamas and Islamic Jihad leaders, but also called on all
Palestinians to close their ranks to fight the "humiliating
policy" of Israel.
</P>
<P>
Danny Naveh, Israel's Cabinet secretary, warned that it was a
big mistake for Arafat to appease the militant groups. "It makes
a very, very big question mark about the future of the peace
process, and about whether the PNA is a partner for peace or
not," he said in an interview with the state television.
</P>
<P>
"And we expected the PNA not to have such dialogue with those
organizations, but to do whatever it can in order to fight these
organizations in order to prevent further violence and
terrorism," he added.
</P>
<P>
Israeli security officials expressed the worry that the PNA's
dialogue with Hamas and other opposition groups could be Arafat's
tactic approval for more terror attacks against Israel.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Wednesday, David Bar-Illan, media adviser to
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, said that Arafat
should launch an all-out war against terrorism instead of
appeasing the militant groups.
</P>
<P>
Following the July 30 suicide bombings in Jerusalem that
killed 16 people, Israel imposed a total closure on the
Palestinian territories, barring Palestinian workers from working
in Israel and halted transferring millions of dollars in tax
revenues to the PNA. The sanctions have inflicted economic
hardships on the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Blasting Israel for humiliating the Palestinian people through
these sanctions, Arafat warned that "all options are open... We
can erase everything and start anew."
</P>
<P>
Hamas leader Abdul Aziz Rantisi interpreted the meeting as a
call for "resistance of every kind" to confront Israeli
occupation. "We must leave the Oslo plan, which Israel uses as a
weapon to fight us," he said.
</P>
<P>
Rantisi thanked Arafat for not bowing to the Unite States and
Israel to crack down toughly on Hamas activities. He also
reiterated the demand for the PNA to relase jailed Hamas
activists, for the return of all Palestinians and confrontation
with Israeli settlements.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, the U.S. government also lashed out at the PNA
for having dialogue with the militant groups. State Department
spokesman James Rubin said that Arafat had promised to fight
terrorism, and the U.S. would judge him by his deeds.


22/08/97 6:1 GMT

