<HEADLINE> Turkish Cypriot Leader Rejects Accusation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf
Denktash today categorically rejected U.N. Security Council term
president's accusation that Turkish Cypriots impede the Cyprus
peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Denktash made the remarks following Wednesday's statement by
the council President Jone Weston from Britain criticizing Turkish
Cypriots for the failure of the talks held last Friday in
Switzerland, according to the semi-official Anatolia News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a reception in Nicosia, the Turkish Cypriot leader
said that he did not think that Diego Cordovez,
U.N. Secretary-General's Special Representative to Cyprus, will
agree with such a statement.
</P>
<P>
Weston had reportedly said in his speech that Cypriot President
Glafcos Clerides showed flexibility during the negotiations but
the Turkish Cypriot side impeded the substantive process "by
bringing preconditions to the table."
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot government and the U.N. blamed the Turkish Cypriot
side for blocking the talks by insisting on European Union's drop
of its planned accession talks with Cyprus as a precondition to
the Cyprus negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Denktash also accused the British representative to the U.N. of
openly shielding Clerides, saying that Weston seemed to be the
mouthpiece of the Greek Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
Stressing that the Turkish Cypriots will not allow anyone to
control the peace process on the divided island, Denktash said,"
we will not be submissive towards injustice."
</P>
<P>
He said that he will submit his views concerning this issue to
Cordovez, adding that it is better not to go to any negotiating
tables if the Turkish Cypriots are always unjustly accused of
undermining the protracted peace process.
</P>
<P>
Turkish diplomatic sources also expressed their dissatisfaction
with the British representative's remarks against the Turkish
Cypriots, saying that they did not understand why Weston made such
a statement.
</P>
<P>
The talks in the Swiss town of Glion-sur-Montreux was a
continuation of the first round of peace talks between Denktash
and Clerides held from July 9 to 12, at Troutbeck, near New York
under the auspices of the U.N..
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus problem has remained unresolved since 1974 when
Turkish troops invaded and took over the northern third of the
small Mediterranean island in the wake of a pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. and international community have been trying for
decades to reunite the island state which was divided into Greek
and Turkish communities, but so far no concrete results have
been achieved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
