<HEADLINE> Ukraine to Complete Tax Reforms by End of 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Ukraine will complete its tax
reforms by the end of 1997, Ukrainian Minister of Economy Viktor
Suslov said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Suslov told a press conference that Feder Yaroshenko, acting
chairman of the State Tax Administration, has presented a package
of 19 draft tax reform laws, which aim to boost the country's
budget revenues by broadening the base for taxation.
</P>
<P>
"All these laws will be approved by the parliament by the end
of 1997, although some of the laws will be introduced next year,"
Suslov said.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Prime Minister Sergi Tigipko said that the cabinet has
selected some of the 19 draft laws to form the basis of the 1998
draft budget plan.
</P>
<P>
Among them are the draft amendment to the Law on Taxation of
Enterprise Profits, the draft amendments to the Law on Value-Added
Tax, and the draft amendments to the Ukrainian Law on Excise
Duties.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine's present tax laws impose heavy burden on legal
businessman while leaving considerable loopholes for illegal ones
to evade taxes.
</P>
<P>
Ukrainian Prime Minister Valeriy Pustovoitenko also urged the
government to exercise strict control over tax collection.
</P>
<P>
"The high tax burden shouldered by manufacturers remains a
difficult problem," said the prime minister at a cabinet meeting
today.
</P>
<P>
According to Pustovoitenko, this year's tax revenues had
increased to about 14 billion hryvnas (7.7 billion U.S. dollars)
by August 14, 14 million hryvnas (7.7 million U.S. dollars) more
than the same period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
It is hoped the new package of tax reforms will recover 2.4
billion hryvnas (1.3 billion U.S. dollars) more from the country's
shadow economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
