<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Western Scholars Point to Flourishing Tibetan Culture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Two Western scholars attending
the ongoing '97 Beijing Seminar on Tibetan Studies refuted various
Western arguments that the Chinese government has destroyed
Tibet's traditional culture by presenting evidence clearly showing
that Tibetan traditional culture is flourishing.
</P>
<P>
Professor Colin Mackerras, a Tibetologist who serves as the
president of Griffith University and director of the Modern Asian
Studies School in Australia, commented that "Tibetan culture is
stronger than ever before.
</P>
<P>
"I sincerely believe that the Chinese government is extending
every possible effort to preserve Tibetan culture.
</P>
<P>
"Tibet's traditions are unlikely to die out in the foreseeable
future."
</P>
<P>
Mackerras added that Tibetan traditions are stronger in the
1990s and are, in fact, stronger than virtually any other
traditional culture in China.
</P>
<P>
The professor has visited the Tibet Autonomous Region and
Tibetan communities in neighboring provinces twice.
</P>
<P>
He voiced total disagreement with those who advocate the need
to split Tibet from China to maintain the region's distinctive
traditions.
</P>
<P>
"It would be economically unsound and dangerous to split Tibet
from China," said Mackerras.
</P>
<P>
Richard Strassberg, a professor of Eastern cultures, said
that Tibetan culture, especially the theatrical arts, has many
links with Chinese culture.
</P>
<P>
"Certain widespread forms of storytelling like Tibetan
`Lama-mani' and Tang Dynasty 'Bianwen' share particular
similarities," according to Strassberg, a professor in the Chinese
Department of East Asian Languages at the University of
California, Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
Similarly, various drama performances with Buddhist themes
spread from Tibet to other parts of China along with the spread of
Tibetan Buddhism, said Strassberg.
</P>
<P>
The two professors, both of whom have studied the Eastern
Cultures for many years, are special guests at the seminar
attended by more than 130 Tibetologists from around the world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
