<HEADLINE> Palestinian Officials Stress National Unity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian officials today
underscored national unity at a critical juncture of the
Israeli-Palestinian relations, JMCC, an East Jerusalem-based
Palestinian press service reported.
</P>
<P>
"National unity is what characterizes the current stage" of
the Israeli-Palestinian relations," Speaker of the Palestinian
National Council Salim Zanoun said at the second-day session
of the national unity dialogue held between the Palestinian
National Authority (PNA) and opposition groups, including Hamas
and Islamic Jihad.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian national unity dialogue, which was initiated
by PNA President Yasser Arafat a few years ago, was resumed in
Gaza Wednesday and continued in the West Bank city of Ramallah
today.
</P>
<P>
Critic of the Israeli and U.S. negative reactions to the
meeting, Zanoun stated that the Palestinians refuse to obey
instructions from the outside and totally reject Israeli
dictations.
</P>
<P>
The dialogue has angered the Israeli government that has
turned the screws at the PNA since the suicide bombing attack on
July 30.
</P>
<P>
Nabil Abu Rdeineh, advisor to Arafat, said that it was most
important for all to take a unified stand under one command to
deal with Israeli pressure.
</P>
<P>
Hani Hassan, a senior Fatah official, called on all Islamic
and national forces and the PNA to forge a national unity. He
asked for a regular monthly meeting to be chaired by Arafat to
enhance constant coordination to face challenges.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Speaker of the Palestinian Council Mitri Abu Eitan
said that the Israeli-imposed total closure "is now confronted
by the Palestinian national unity, a guarantee for dwarfing
occupation schemes."
</P>
<P>
Bashir Al-Barghouti, a senior official of the Palestinian
People's Party, called for a confrontation against the Netanyahu
government's attempts to destroy the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Abdel Rahim Malouh, a representative of the Popular Front for
Liberation of Palestine, accused Israel of pursuing a policy
designed to starve the Palestinian people and of forcing the PNA
to accept facts it created on the ground.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the need to confront Israel's policy of land
confiscation and Judizing the occupied East Jerusalem, and to
back up the PNA.
</P>
<P>
Today's session was interrupted for 10 minutes when
participants led by Arafat left the meeting hall to meet with
Palestinian medical workers, who gathered in front of the
headquarters of the PLO to express their support for Arafat's
call for national unity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
