<HEADLINE> Malaysia to Generate, Distribute Power for Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, August 22 (Xinhua) -- A Malaysian electric power
company has reached agreement with a Myanmar state-run counterpart
to form a joint venture for generating and distributing electric
power in southern Myanmar, official newspaper The New Light of
Myanmar reported today.
</P>
<P>
This is Myanmar's first joint venture agreement with foreign
firms in power generation and distribution.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached here Thursday between Genting Power
Holding Ltd. of Malaysia and Myanmar Electric Power Enterprise.
</P>
<P>
Before the joint venture was initiated, Myanmar had been
cooperating with foreign firms in getting technical know-how and
equipment for building power stations and power distribution in
the country.
</P>
<P>
In May, three South Korean firms -- Daewoo, LG International
and Hyundai -- agreed to render assistance in the development of
Myanmar's electric power distribution under the Economic
Development Corporation Fund.
</P>
<P>
At present, Japan's Kajima Corporation is undertaking a
280-megawatt Paunglaung hydropower project under a contract
reached in May last year.
</P>
<P>
A number of foreign firms which have signed memorandums of
understanding with Myanmar are also undertaking feasibility
studies on building hydropower stations in the country. They
include Daewoo (South Korea), Hunan (China), oil group UNOCAL (the
United States), TOTAL (France), Mitsui (Japan), and developer
groups Marubeni (Japan), MDX (Thailand) and Italian-Thai
Development Public Co.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar has built three hydropower stations and three
natural-gas power stations since 1988, which generated 4.256
billion kilowatt-hours of electricity in fiscal 1996-97, 200
million kilowatt-hours more than the previous fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
The country also extended power transmission and distribution
lines to 21,054 kilometers in the fiscal year, bringing
electricity to 320 towns and 1,087 villages, according to official
statistics.
</P>
<P>
The statistics also show that Malaysian investment in Myanmar
ranks fifth after Britain, Singapore, Thailand and the United
States. By the end of July this year, Malaysia had invested a
total of 524.17 million U.S. dollars in 23 permitted projects in
real estate, hotel and tourism, wood-based industry, manufacturing
and oil and gas.  
</P>
</TEXT>
