<HEADLINE> Thailand Cracks Down on Stock Market Offenders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's Securities and
Exchange Commission (SEC) has imposed penalties on 68 companies
and executives that violated stock trading rules during the first
half of this year, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The SEC levied a total fine of some 8 million baht (about
267,000 U.S. dollars) on the 68 offenders, including the 42 firms
which failed to submit financial statements to the SEC within the
specified period.
</P>
<P>
Other companies fined include six firms selling securities not
in their possession, one failing to follow the required balance
sheet form, one lending additional margin loans without additional
collateral, and one failing to report its securities trading.
</P>
<P>
Some executives or dealers were fined for various offenses on
the market. Their offenses include failing to report their
companies' holding in other companies, failing to sign contracts
with clients, using inside information, or misleading others by
quoting a securities price at an unusual level.
</P>
<P>
The crackdown was seen as one of the government steps to
strengthen the financial discipline.  
</P>
</TEXT>
