<HEADLINE> Second World Forum of Ukrainians Opens in Kiev </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The Second World Forum of
Ukrainians which aims to promote the Ukrainian statehood on the
world stage, opened in Kiev Thursday.
</P>
<P>
About 450 delegates and 400 guests from 47 countries are
attending the week-long forum.
</P>
<P>
"It's a special event in the modern history of Ukraine,"
Ukrainian President Leonid Kuchma said at the forum.
</P>
<P>
Kuchma declared that the time had come for members of the
Ukrainian diaspora to change from supporting individual
politicians, political parties and public organizations to
assisting national policies.
</P>
<P>
He said this would enhance the assertion of Ukraine's
independence, democracy and market reforms.
</P>
<P>
"Ukraine has made substantial breakthroughs in its
international relations with the aim of strengthening its
nationhood and sovereignty," Kuchma noted.
</P>
<P>
He said that Ukraine has become a fully-fledged and influential
member of the international community and its independence is
recognized by the world.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine gained the Council of Europe membership in 1995 and
established strategic partnerships with countries including the
United States, Canada and Poland.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine has signed broad-based agreements with its neighbors
including Russia, Belarus, Poland and Romania, enabling it to
resolve old feuds and pave the way for bilateral cooperation,
Kuchma said.
</P>
<P>
However, the Ukrainian president, in particular, accused the
European Union and the United States of conducting discriminatory
trade and economic policies against Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
He complained that access of Ukrainian goods to the European
and world markets was hindered by various restrictions,
antidumping policies and other protectionist measures.
</P>
<P>
High-quality and competitive Ukrainian metallurgical products
were squeezed out of the American market by excessive antidumping
duties, Kuchma said.
</P>
<P>
He called on the Ukrainian diaspora in the West to assist in
resolving this problem. 
</P>
