<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Current Account Deficit Up 15 Pct </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's trade in the
1996/1997 fiscal year suffered a higher current account deficit
but analysts say it is still at a safe level.
</P>
<P>
Local newspaper Indonesian Observer reported today that the
higher current account deficit for the period ending April this
year was mainly attributable to decelerating exports of
non-oil/gas commodities.
</P>
<P>
The deficit went up 15 percent from 7 billion U.S. dollars in
1995/96 or 3.4 percent of gross domestic product (GDP) to 8.1
billion dollars in 1996/97 or 3.5 percent of GDP, it said.
</P>
<P>
In the 1996/97 fiscal year, exports rose 4.9 percent to 52
billion dollars from 47.8 billion in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
"The growth rate was lower compared with the last fiscal year
when it reached 13.3 percent," the report said.
</P>
<P>
The growth rate of non-oil/gas exports declined from 17.1
percent to 5.7 percent, while oil/gas exports rose to 15 percent
from 3.4 percent, it said, adding that non-oil/gas exports made up
a 75.5 percent share of total exports in the 1996/97 fiscal year,
compared with 77.8 percent in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the growth of imports declined from 21.6 percent to
10.4 percent due to slower growth of non-oil imports. Indonesia's
non-oil/gas imports grew 9.4 percent in the last fiscal year,
compared with 23.4 percent previously.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian government has become more aggressive in
boosting exports and discouraging imports to reign in the current
account deficit.
</P>
<P>
In July this year, the government announced deregulatory
measures covering the reduction of tariffs for goods imported for
"export-oriented" investments and the simplification of investment
procedures by reducing the number of taxes to a minimal level.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
