<HEADLINE> Feature: Economic Progress in China Is Great </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 21 (Xinhua) -- He tells stories of China's
past and present, shedding lights on historical changes in the
world's most populous country; and he works hard to make
Americans understand better the economic progress, the uphill
fight for more prosperity and business opportunities in that
country.
</P>
<P>
Robert A. Kapp, a specialist on modern China, used to teach in
universities before he came to lead the Washington Council on
International Trade in the Washington State.
</P>
<P>
He became president of the U.S.-China Business Council in April
1994, and that has made him more popular and consulted with on
China.
</P>
<P>
"I think all Americans understand that since 1978, particularly
under the policy initiated by (the late Chinese leader) Deng
Xiaoping, China has made extraordinarily great economic progress,"
Robert said in his downtown office.
</P>
<P>
"We look with great admiration at the nation of more than one
billion people enjoy year after year 10 percent economic growth,"
he noted after citing the corruptive empires and the devastating
impact of foreign invasions in Chinese history.
</P>
<P>
He even spoke in Chinese of China's current policy of "economic
reform and opening to the outside world." He told us he had
studied a recent speech by Chinese President Jiang Zemin six times
to try to understand it better.
</P>
<P>
"Beyond the economy itself, we recognize the great achievements
China has managed to accomplish in raising a hundred or more
million people from absolute poverty...rapid modernization of
urban life," said Robert, who is now representing some 300
American companies trading with China.
</P>
<P>
He believed that China is of great interest to a lot of
Americans, while many other countries are not. "Whether it is good
or bad, history will tell," he said, referring to the ongoing
debate on China in the United States.
</P>
<P>
The business leader has shown up in four congressional hearings
to defend China's Most Favored Nation (MFN) trade status. When
accused of "lobbying for China" by some, he rebutted the charges,
saying it is also in the interest of the United States.
</P>
<P>
As an advocate of better overall ties with China, Robert calls
for solutions to the difficulties China faces.
</P>
<P>
The problems, which he said might be caused by rapid economic
growth, include the widening gap in people's incomes, the
disparity between the coastal and the interior areas, the
unsatisfactory performance of the state-owned enterprises and some
social problems.
</P>
<P>
China has done a good job in international monetary
institutions, but in the field of trade, the pace is relatively
slow, he remarked to us.
</P>
<P>
He said China will undoubtedly carry on its economic reform and
enjoy sustained development in the next century. And it is
extremely important for China to further integrate itself with the
outside world, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
