<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Personal Income Tax Revenue Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, August 22 (Xinhua) -- China scored a 42.5 percent
increase in personal income tax revenues in the first half of this
year, according to a national tax conference.
</P>
<P>
The personal income tax revenue in the January-June period came
to 12.34 billion yuan (about 1.48 billion US dollars), Li Yonggui,
chief economist of the State Administration of Taxation, told a
national tax conference held recently in Huangshan City, Anhui
Province.
</P>
<P>
China's personal income tax revenue has been growing markedly
each year since a revised personal income tax law was implemented
in 1994. The growth rate for the 1994-1996 period was 60.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
This year China expects to collect 24 billion yuan in personal
income tax, up 24 percent from 1996.
</P>
<P>
Taxation agencies at all levels should beef up their efforts to
collect personal income taxes, Li said, adding that cases of tax
evasion must be investigated and tax evaders punished. 
</P>
</TEXT>
