<HEADLINE> Colombian Rebels Release 17 Political Leaders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The National
Liberation Army (ELN) of Colombia released 17 political leaders
today in San Pablo town in the department of Bolivar, the military
sources announced.
</P>
<P>
The released politicians, who were seized by the guerrillas
last Friday, including four candidates for the mayorship and four
council members, were handed over to an humanitarian commission
made up of members of the Red Cross International Committee and
the People's Defenders.
</P>
<P>
The commander of the military forces, General Manuel Jose
Bonett, said that today's case, the same as the 30 others who had
been prisoners of the ELN, was not a kidnapping, but rather an
appointment with the guerrillas they were forced to comply with.
</P>
<P>
The ELN and the Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia (FARC)
announced in April that they would sabotage the October
election. They have called about 50 mayors, councilmen and
candidates in the departments of Antioquia and Bolivar "to settle
accounts" since June.
</P>
<P>
The 17 political leaders were "invited" by the insurgents to
accompany them to the mountain or to the jungle. The politicians
said the "appointments" were mandatory, though they made no death
threats if they were not obeyed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
