<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Rupiah, Stock Market Continue to Gain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's rupiah surged
Thursday by another 100 points against the U.S. dollar and stock
prices rose 1.67 percent.
</P>
<P>
Spot rupiah, which opened at 2,780/2,810, strengthened and
broke the resistance level of 2,700 to reach 2,650 in morning
trading and closed at 2,670/2,690, according to dealers here
today.
</P>
<P>
They said the current tight monetary policy had forced local
players to sell their dollar to meet their rupiah obligations.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, share prices on the Jakarta Stock Exchange ended
higher Thursday as the strengthening of the rupiah boosted
sentiment, stock brokers said.
</P>
<P>
The Jakarta Composite Index again broke the 600 level, jumping
9.89 points or 1.67 percent to close at 603.06.
</P>
<P>
Coordinating Minister for Economy and Fiancee Saleh Afiff said
Thursday the government had achieved its first target to bring the
rupiah below the upper level of Bank Indonesia's now defunct
intervention band (2,378-2,682 rupiah against the U.S. dollar).
</P>
<P>
The rupiah fell to an historical low of 3,045 against the
greenback after Bank Indonesia, the central bank, floated the
rupiah last week in the wake of sustained speculative attacks on
regional currencies.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah started recovering following the central bank's
increase of interest rates Tuesday. The bank raised its one-week
Bank Indonesia certificates (SBI) from 10.5 percent to 20 percent,
two-week rates from 11 percent to 22 percent, one-month rates from
11.625 percent to 30 percent and three-month rates from 11.5
percent to 28 percent.
</P>
<P>
Afiff said that the government would continue to tighten rupiah
for some time until market jitters calmed down and the rupiah
stabilized.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
