<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State Assets Expands in China's Guangzhou </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, August 22 (Xinhua) -- The value of state assets in
Guangzhou, capital city of South China's Guangdong Province, has
been growing steadily, according to official figures.
</P>
<P>
A total of 3,710 enterprises in Guangzhou were involved in an
annual campaign to register property rights of the state-owned
assets. Final results show that by the end of 1996, the
enterprises had assets valued at 259.4 billion yuan (about 31.2
billion US dollars), of which state assets accounted for 28
percent. In another analysis, state assets made up 87 percent of
the net asset value.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the total assets of the enterprises in Guangzhou
that possess or operate state-owned assets shot up 29 percent from
the 1995 figure, whereas the net asset value surged 44 percent
year-on-year.
</P>
<P>
The state-owned sector still plays a vital role in the economy
of Guangzhou, though its ratio has gone down somewhat since China
initiated the policy of the reform and opening-up in 1979, experts
here say.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong is a showcase of China's market economy reform.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
