<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Seminar Held On Chinese, Japanese Characters in Northeast China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, August 22 (Xinhua) -- More than 100 Chinese and
Japanese graphologists, linguists, calligraphers and historians
have discussed the characteristics of writing systems of the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
They also expressed views on the influence that the writing
systems have had on cultural development, during a seminar held
recently in this capital of northeast China's Liaoning Province.
</P>
<P>
The two countries have had a long history in cultural
exchanges. Japan based its unique writing system on a combination
of Chinese characters and ancient culture and Latin.
</P>
<P>
Chinese characters have played an important role in the spread
of Chinese civilization to other parts of the world. The study of
Chinese characters is now popular internationally.
</P>
<P>
During recent years, experts from each country have studied the
origin and evolution of their characters and the differences
between them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970822.0283 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese, American Students Get Together at Nixon Library </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Seventy Chinese high school
students met and exchanged views with their American counterparts
today at the Richard Nixon Library and Birthplace in Yorba Linda,
California.
</P>
<P>
This was a closing event of a month-long "Youth Summit" to mark
the 25th anniversary of the signing of the Sino-U.S. Shanghai
Communique. The event was sponsored by the Chinese People's
Association for Friendship with Foreign Countries (CPAFFC) and
People to People International.
</P>
<P>
At the library, the Chinese students, together with southern
Californian high school students, watched two documentaries,
toured the library and listened to lectures.
</P>
<P>
They also broke into small groups to discuss the far-reaching
significance of the Shanghai Communique on Sino-U.S. relations in
the 21st century. The signing of the communique in Shanghai in
1972 marked the beginning of the normalization of relations
between China and the United States.
</P>
<P>
As part of the "Young Summit," 75 American students from 22
states visited Shanghai between July and August, where they
listened to lectures on Sino-U.S. relations and exchanged views
with Chinese students.
</P>
<P>
"As these young people...get to know each other and exchange
views about the things that divide them and the things that bring
them together, they help continue the peace-making work that began
in 1972," said John Taylor, executive director of the Richard
Nixon Library and Birthplace Foundation.
</P>
<P>
Agreeing with him, Li Xiaolin, CPAFFC deputy president and head
of the Chinese delegation, said the exchange program enhanced
mutual understanding and friendship between students of the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese students had previously spent six days in Hawaii,
and will leave for home at the end of this week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
