<DOCNO> XIE19970822.0284 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poor Families Receive International Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 22 (Xinhua) -- Poor rural families in China are
receiving aid from different countries through the partnership
between the Chinese Association for International Understanding
(CAFIU) and Plan International, today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
The poverty relief programs, which have already started in
Beijing and Shaanxi Province, will expand to the provinces of
Gansu and Qinghai and the Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region within two
years, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
A secondary school has been set up in Binxian County, Shaanxi
Province, just in time for the new school year. The building,
which is said to be the best in the area, cost 670,000 yuan
(80,700 US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The project in Shaanxi is still developing and will at least
double the size of the pilot scheme in Yanqing, a mountainous
county in northern Beijing, said Don Mcphee, Plan International's
representative in China.
</P>
<P>
Half of the 500,000 US dollars spent since 1995 has been used
in Yanqing's projects, such as improving the water supply,
providing school library books and training teachers.
</P>
<P>
The rest of the fund went to help 3,000 poor families with
children between the ages of six and 12. It was used to help the
local people build greenhouses, raise domestic animals and grow
medicinal plants and fruit trees.
</P>
<P>
The families pay part of the cost for the projects.
</P>
<P>
"Local people will handle the business with care when they have
a share in the investment," said Liu Yanfu, an official with
CAFIU. Staff from CAFIU/PLAN make weekly visits to the rural area
to make sure the programs are operating smoothly. Professional
auditors are invited each year to examine projects accounting
records. enditem

nnnn
</P>
</TEXT>
