<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, August 22 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD -- A key leader in Afghanistan's anti-Taliban
alliance, Abdulrahim Ghaforzai, was killed Thursday in an air
crash, reports said today.
</P>
<P>
Ghaforzai, who was selected as the "prime minister" of the
northern alliance only last week, was killed on his way to
central Bamyan province when his plane lost control and crashed,
the reports quoted an alliance spokesman as saying.
(Pakistan-Afghanistan-Air Crash)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The U.S. Navy will declassify its submarine data
from the height of the Cold War and the release will be a boon to
research on climate and the spread of pollution, a research group
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The data was gathered by U.S. nuclear submarines on routine
operations in the Arctic Ocean during 1957-1982, the U.S. Arctic
Research Commission said in a statement. (US-Navy-Declassification)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The U.S. government deficit shrank by about
two-thirds in the first 10 months of fiscal 1997 comparing with
the same period a year ago, the U.S. Treasury Department reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The department said that the deficit so far in the fiscal year
ending September 30 totaled 36.7 billion dollars, 64 percent below
the 100.9 billion registered in the same period of fiscal 1996.
(US-Deficit-Down)
</P>
