<HEADLINE> Popov Retains Fourth Consecutive Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Alexander Popov of Russia showed
his Olympic champion style to win the title in the men's 100
meters freestyle at the European Swimming Championships in
Seville, Spain on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The victory not only accomplished his fourth consecutive
European 100 title, but showed his comeback from the shadow of
last year's accident in a Moscow street.
</P>
<P>
The 25-year-old Popov clocked in 49.09 seconds, the fastest
time in the world this year and also set a European championship
record.
</P>
<P>
The Russian swept both 50 meters and 100 meters freestyle
titles at the 1996 Atlanta and 1992 Barcelona Olympics, and
snapped almost all of the two events in the international
competitions since 1991.
</P>
<P>
However, triple Olympic champion Michelle de Bruin's dream of
getting five individual titles faded when Germany's Dagmar Hase
stole the gold away in the women's 400 meters freestyle.
</P>
<P>
De Bruin, who won the 400 individual medley on Tuesday and
the 200 freestyle on Wednesday, had to settle with the silver at
4:10.50 while 27-year-old Hase finished 0.92 seconds ahead.
</P>
<P>
Vladimir Selkov of Russia made the first successful individual
title defence when he took the men's 200m backstroke crown for the
third time in succession at 1:59.21, edging Italy's Emanuele
Merisi by 0.42 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Antje Buschschulte of Germany won the women's 100m backstroke at
1:01.74, and followed by Bucharest-born Roxana Maracineanu of
France at 1:01.84 and German Sandra Voelker 1:02.23, winner of
Tuesday's 100m freestyle.
</P>
<P>
Germany won the women's 4x100m freestyle relay in 3:41.91 with
silver for Sweden and bronze for Russia.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
