<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South China Province Reports 32.6 Percent Tax Revenue Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 22 (Xinhua) -- The industrial and commercial
tax revenue of South China's Guangdong Province, an economic
powerhouse bordering Hong Kong, has been growing by an average
annual rate of more than 30 percent in the past five years.
</P>
<P>
In the first half of this year, Guangdong collected nearly 48.3
billion yuan in industrial and commercial taxes, up 32.6 percent
from the same 1996 period.
</P>
<P>
A provincial taxation official contributed the surge in the tax
revenue to a rapid expansion of tax resources in recent years.
</P>
<P>
The latest statistics indicate that Guangdong's industrial and
commercial tax base had included 10.2 million enterprises by the
end of last year, 230,000 more than in 1990.
</P>
<P>
The official said that the number of overseas-funded
enterprises, a major source of industrial and commercial taxes,
had reached 49,726 by the end of 1996. Industrial and commercial
taxes collected from such enterprises were valued at 18.5 billion
yuan last year, about 22.3 percent of Guangdong's yearly tax
revenue.
</P>
<P>
A higher rate of collection is another factor behind the rapid
growth in Guangdong's industrial and commercial tax revenue, the
official said. He added that more than 21,000 cases of tax
violation were investigated last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
