<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Shanghai People Marry Foreigners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, August 22 (Xinhua) -- More than 2,100 Chinese people
in Shanghai married foreigners last year, 67 percent more than in
1991, according to a survey by the city's civil affairs bureau.
</P>
<P>
These inter-racial marriages accounted for 3.5 percent of the
city's total number of marriages last year, compared with 1.9
percent in 1991, according to the survey.
</P>
<P>
Some 168,000 people registered for marriage last year in this
economically-vibrant city at the mouth of the Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
Far more Chinese women than men marry foreigners, and more and
more of the couples are setting up homes in Shanghai rather than
moving overseas.
</P>
<P>
The age gap between the spouses is also narrowing.
</P>
<P>
However, the survey finds, marriages between Shanghai people
and foreigners have also been breaking up at a faster
rate in the past few years. The divorce rate from such marriages
last year more than doubled the figure from 1991.
</P>
<P>
Over 24,600 couples divorced in Shanghai last year, a rise of
43.9 percent over 1991.
</P>
<P>
A sociologist said that Shanghai is not unique in the country
in witnessing a boom in inter-racial marriages and accelerating
divorce rates, adding that Chinese marriages were more stable
before 1978, the year the country opened to the outside world and
initiated economic reforms.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
