<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sudanese Government, Opposition to Hold Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The Sudanese government has
agreed to participate in the proposed peace meeting with rebels in
South African capital Pretoria at the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters today, the Sudanese Minister of Foreign
Affairs Ali Osman Mohamed Taha said Khartoum has received an
invitation to participate in the meeting with the Southern
Sudanese rebel leader John Garang, which was called for by South
African President Nelson Mandela.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese government has also agreed to attend another
meeting with Ugandan President Yoweri Musevini.
</P>
<P>
Taha further stated that a number of African Heads of State
would likely take part in these meetings, such as Zimbabwean
President Robert Mugabe.
</P>
<P>
The minister pointed out that the agenda of the meeting with
Musevini includes relations between the Sudan and Uganda, and the
alleged role of Uganda in supporting the war in Southern Sudan. On
the other hand, the agenda of the talks with Garang covers all
issues related to peace.
</P>
<P>
The minister also said that the meetings aim at rapprochement
between the various parties.
</P>
<P>
Information available to the Sudanese government, he said,
reveals that all invited parties have agreed to attend, including
Garang.
</P>
<P>
Mandela has recently announced the arrangement of the meeting
between Sudanese President Omar Bashir and Garang in the presence
of Musevini to push forward the peace process in the Sudan.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese president visited South Africa earlier this month
and had talks with Mandela. On his part, Mandela had appealed for
cease-fire in Southern Sudan and for peace negotiations to end the
14-year-old war between the Sudanese government troops and the
Garang-led rebel forces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
