<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Gymnasts Take First Gold Medal at Universiade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CATANIA, Italy, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Thanks to changes to
cometition schedules, the Chinese delegation won the first gold medal
of the 19th World University Games here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
According to the original schedules, the men's team foil will be
the first final of the games, just before the final of the men's
gymnastics team event.
</P>
<P>
But the organizers changed the schedule of the fencing tournament
several times on Thursday. Shortly before the final, it began to rain
and the organizers had to move the competitions from outdoor venue
back into an exhibition hall.
</P>
<P>
The delay of the fencing final enabled the Chinese men's gymnastics
team to win the first gold medal of the games. But the competition
itself is not easy for the Chinese team which includes of three
national champions.
</P>
<P>
After the first five rounds, the Chinese team led second-placed
Japan by a margin of only 0.2 points. In the final round, the Chinese
gymnasts shrugged off the pressure and wrapped up the competitions
with a total of 167.450 points.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese team, which will participate in the forthcoming world
championships in Switzerland, took the silver medal with a total of
165.850 points, followed by the Romanian team with 165.550 points.
</P>
<P>
Xiao Yinchun, coach of the Chinese team, said after the
competition: "It is very pleasant for us to win the first gold medal
of the Universiade for the Chinese delegation. Our gymnasts did well
in the competitions."
</P>
<P>
In the men's foil individual finals, the only other finals of the
day, twice world champion Rolando Samuel Tucker of Cuba overwhelmed
Sergy Golubytsky of Ukraine 15-13 to win the title.
</P>
<P>
Golubytsky, the silver medalist at the Atlanta Olympic Games and
the newly-crowned world champion at last month's Cape Town world
championships, finished runner-up while China's Wang Haibin and Vadirm
Ajoupov of Russia tied for the bronze medal.
</P>
<P>
The men's and women's volleyball and women's basketball
competitions also began on Thursday. The Chinese female cagers lost
to the Cuban team 108-62 while the Chinese women spikers won their
first match by defeating underdogs Algerian team 15-13, 15-2 and
15-11.
</P>
<P>
In the tennis tournament, the first round of men's and women's
singles have been played at Palermo on Thursday. Top-seeded Wang
Shi-Ting of Chinese Taipei enjoyed a bye in the women's singles first
round while the men's top seed Yoon Yong Il of South Korea beat Magnus
Bergman of Sweden 6-1, 6-1 to advance into the second round.
</P>
<P>
There will be two gold medals at stake on Friday. China is among
the favorites to win the women's gymnastics team event while Italian
athletes are favored to win the title of the women's individual epee
title. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970822.0310 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists Warn Greece of Possible Strong Quakes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Scientists today warned of the
possibility that Greece could be hit by strong earthquakes over
the next 13 years.
</P>
<P>
The scientists made the warning while attending the 29th world
seismology conference which opened Monday in the northern Greek
port city of Thessaloniki.
</P>
<P>
They made the prediction on the basis of observations and
statistical data processed by a research team of the geophysics
laboratory of Thessaloniki University.
</P>
<P>
They stressed that Greece had entered from 1996 a period of
heightened seismic activity which was expected to last until the
year 2010.
</P>
<P>
The university research team, using a long-term quake
prediction method, said that it had identified 25 areas posing a
high risk from the point of view of seismic activity.
</P>
<P>
Up to 27 earthquakes of over six on the Richter scale could
rock Greece by the year 2010, said George Karakaisis, professor of
seismology of Thessaloniki University.
</P>
<P>
The Greek government had been reportedly urged by scientists to
increase its anti-seismic protection measures.
</P>
<P>
Scientists say that Greece's geology and its location at the
junction of several tectonic plates make it especially prone to
shifts that cause tremors and quakes.
</P>
<P>
The south is believed to be Greece's most quake-prone region,
with all but seven of the 30 deadliest quakes since 1800 having
occurred there.
</P>
<P>
The most recent occurred on June 15, 1995 in the northern
Peloponnese town of Aegio, where dozens of buildings were razed and
26 people killed by the 6.4 magnitude tremor.
</P>
<P>
The 10-day conference has drawn over 1,000 seismology experts
from around the world to discuss the quake-prediction methods.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
