<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bundesbank Leaves Key Interest Rates Intact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The German central bank, the
Bundesbank, today left the country's two benchmark interest rates
unchanged as expected by money markets.
</P>
<P>
The discount rate and Lombard rate have been left unchanged at
historical lows of 2.5 percent and 4.5 percent respectively since
April 1996. The country's another key rate, the securities
repurchase rate, also remains at 3.0 percent since a year ago.
</P>
<P>
The Bundesbank, however, decided two weeks ago to review the
repurchase rate week by week instead of the conventional interval
of two weeks. This tactic has proved to be effective to check the
German mark's steep decline against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
It is widely believed that a rate hike in Germany carries the
risk that it could choke economic growth and undermine the
government's effort to combat record high unemployment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
