<BODY>
<HEADLINE> School Enrollment in US Increasing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 21 (Xinhua) -- School enrollment in the
United States this fall will reach to a record 52.2 million and
the trend is expected to continue through 2007 as a result of
delayed marriage and child-bearing of baby boomers and some other
factors, a U.S. government report said today.
</P>
<P>
According to an Education Department report, the 52.2 million
children attending school this fall will be an increase of 800,000
over last year, mostly teenagers because enrollment among
elementary students increased from fall 1985 to fall 1997.
</P>
<P>
The report said the enrollment in public and private schools is
expected to reach its peak at 54.3 million in 2007.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, from this fall until 2007, public
schools can expect a 13 percent increase in grades 9-12, a 5
percent increase in grades 6-8 and a 1 percent decrease in grades
1-5.
</P>
<P>
The report attributed the rise to several reasons, including
immigration, the delay in marriage and child-bearing among baby
boomers, high birth rates among minorities and longer students
stay in school. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970822.0314 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Finances Infrastructure Improvement in Jordan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank today approved
a 30 million U.S. dollar loan to Jordan for the Community
Infrastructure Project (CIP).
</P>
<P>
The CIP is a component of the government's Social Productivity
Program which is a longer term, multi-dimensional operation that
is designed to lift all households above the poverty line.
</P>
<P>
The CIP is targeted at improving the living conditions of the
1.5 million poor people by providing essential physical and social
infrastructure services, as well as improving the capacity of
selected institutions to deliver these services. The project,
which will be implemented over a three-year period, is expected to
serve as a pilot operation.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank's loan is a dollar-denominated single currency
loan, which is repayable in 17 years, including a four-year grace
period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
