<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cuban Foiler Wins Men's Individual Title at Universiade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
CATANIA, Sicily, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Cuban foiler Rolando Samuel
Tucker edged world champion Sergly Golubytsky of Ukraine to win the
title of the men's individual foil at the 19th World University Games
here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The competition schedule of the fencing tournament has been changed
time and again just on Thursday. It began to rain shortly before
the semi-finals and the organizers rushed to move the competitions
from outdoor venue back into an exhibition hall.
</P>
<P>
Tucker, the 1994 and 1996 world champion, sailed into the final
after beating China's Wang Haibin 15-11 in the semi-finals.
</P>
<P>
Wang, who won the bronze medal at the 1997 World Fencing
Championships held in Cape Town last month, could not resist Tucker's
attacks in the semi-finals and had to be settled with the bronze
medal.
</P>
<P>
"Wang Haibin put up a good performance today though he lost the
match," said Guo Ying, coach of Wang, "Tucker is a very good foiler
and he deserved the victory."
</P>
<P>
Golubytsky, the newly crowned world champion and silver medalist at
the 1996 Atlanta Olympic Games, met a stiff resistence from his former
teammate Vadirm Ajoupov of Russia but managed to sail into the final
with a 15-10 victory.
</P>
<P>
The final between Tucker and Ajoupov was the highlight of the day
as neither one could enlarge the gap to more than two points.
</P>
<P>
The score deadlocked at 13-13 for quite a long time when the more
aggressive Tucker suddenly quickened his pace and scored two straight
points to wrap up the final 15-13.
</P>
<P>
It was the second gold medal of the day. China won the first gold
of the games, the men's team title of the gymnastics tournament after
a thrilling competition earlier on Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
