<DOCNO> XIE19970822.0317 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Waigel Plunges Bonn Into Political Puzzle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The confirmed intention of German
Finance Minister Theo Waigel that he will not hold his unpopular
post after the 1998 general elections has dropped a bombshell in
Bonn and triggered renewed speculations about a possible cabinet
reshuffle by Chancellor Helmut Kohl.
</P>
<P>
Waigel, who has served as finance minister in Kohl's government
since April 1989, surprised political observers Tuesday by saying
that he would quit his current post should Kohl's center-right
ruling coalition be re-elected in the next general elections due
in September 1998.
</P>
<P>
That intention was confirmed today by Kohl who said in a
statement released in Bonn that he was aware of Waigel's plan and
understood his decision.
</P>
<P>
However, both Kohl and Waigel rejected speculations that Waigel
was tired of serving in office, with Waigel indicating that he
would be willing to take over any other top post in the cabinet if
the coalition won the elections.
</P>
<P>
Waigel, 58, has come under heavy pressure for his hard-line
policy to push through fundamental structural reforms and to cut
the huge budget deficit at a time when Germany is plagued by
record high unemployment and the financial plight of making the
grade to join the planned single European currency, the Euro.
</P>
<P>
He also triggered controversies recently for his suggestion of
a cabinet reshuffle which, he said, would boost Kohl's chances to
win the elections.
</P>
<P>
Waigel made the proposal against the background that his party,
the Christian Social Union (CSU), is set to lose one seat in the
cabinet at the end of this year when the Postal Ministry becomes
defunct due to privatization.
</P>
<P>
Kohl, however, rejected a cabinet reshuffle in the near future,
though he also admitted that the dismantlement of the Postal
Ministry would tilt the balance of his government whose 17
ministerial portfolios were shared by his Christian Democratic
Union (CDU), the CSU and the junior partner Free Democratic Party
(FDP).
</P>
<P>
Waigel's latest plan to quit the Finance Ministry after the
elections reinforced the rumors that he might force the FDP to
give up one of its cabinet posts to the CSU.
</P>
<P>
The German newspaper Die Welt quoted unnamed senior officials
as saying today that Kohl might allow Waigel to replace Klaus
Kinkel (FDP) as foreign minister after the elections.
</P>
<P>
Asked to commend on the report by the German media, Waigel
denied that Kohl had made such a promise. But he also said,
"Actually, I believe I'm qualified for any responsible position in
Germany."
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Ministry has traditionally been in the hands of the
FDP. Any takeover is sure to meet its strong resistance. But
Waigel said today that parties could not claim to be heirs to
certain ministries.
</P>
<P>
Whatever happens to Kohl's government, the debates over the
past few days have apparently reinforced German opposition
parties' confidence that they will be able to win the next general
elections.
</P>
<P>
Both the opposition Social Democratic Party (SPD) and the
Greens today repeated their call for an early election. "In such a
hopeless situation, it is better to give up than just to hang on,"
said Werner Schulz, parliamentary general-secretary of the Greens.
</P>
<P>
Analysts meanwhile believe that Kohl will be eventually forced
to reshuffle his cabinet before next September in order to improve
his coalition's popularity for reelection. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
