<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Federal Deficit Declines Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. government deficit
shrank by about two-thirds in the first 10 months of fiscal 1997
comparing with the same period a year ago, the U.S. Treasury
Department reported today.
</P>
<P>
The department said that the deficit so far in the fiscal year
ending September 30 totaled 36.7 billion dollars, 64 percent below
the 100.9 billion registered in the same period of fiscal 1996.
</P>
<P>
So far this year, the Treasury received 1.3 trillion dollars in
revenues, compared to 1.2 trillion a year ago. Spending has
totaled 1.34 trillion dollars, up from 1.3 trillion during the
first 10 months of fiscal 1996.
</P>
<P>
The deficit in July alone totaled 25.6 billion dollars, down
from 26.9 billion a year ago.
</P>
<P>
With tax receipts running 12 percent higher than the previous
year, the shortfall for the fiscal year appeared on track to
become the smallest in nearly a quarter-century, the report said.
</P>
<P>
President Bill Clinton predicted earlier this month the fiscal
1997 deficit would be 37 billion dollars, the smallest since a 6.1
billion dollar shortfall in fiscal 1974. The U.S. Congressional
Budget Office is forecasting a smaller 34 billion deficit.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. federal deficit hit a record 290.4 billion dollars in
fiscal 1992, then slipped to 255 billion the following year, 203.1
billion in fiscal 1994 and 163.9 billion in fiscal 1995. It
dropped to 107.3 billion dollars last year, the smallest since 79
billion in fiscal 1981. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
