<HEADLINE> US Regrets Arafat's Combative Remarks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The United States said today
that it regretted Yasser Arafat's combative language against
Israel, but still believed the Palestinian leader remains a U.S.
partner in pursuing Middle East peace.
</P>
<P>
Arafat attended a "national unity meeting" in Gaza Wednesday
and kissed and applauded leaders of the Hamas and Islamic Holy War
movements. He told the representatives of all factions that
Palestinians were prepared to resume the seven-year uprising
against Israeli occupation. He was referring to the 1987-1994
Palestinian "intifada" or uprising against Israel.
</P>
<P>
"What he did say wasn't particularly constructive in trying to
bring and restore confidence and trust," State Department
spokesman James Rubin said at a briefing.
</P>
<P>
But Rubin also said Arafat "made clear that he does support the
peace process and called on the supporters of the peace process to
work with him for a just and comprehensive peace."
</P>
<P>
"Chairman Arafat is a partner in our quest for peace," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that we have received assurances from Chairman
Arafat that he is going to work with the Israelis to combat
terror and prevent terror," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
