<HEADLINE> UPS Business Less Than Half Normal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 21 (Xinhua) -- United Parcel Service (UPS)
said today it expects to deliver about 45 percent of its normal
package volume on this second day of operations since the end of a
nationwide strike.
</P>
<P>
UPS said several thousand employees have not yet been called
back to work, but didn't give an exact figure.
</P>
<P>
UPS said its drivers picked up approximately 16.2 million
packages Wednesday. It projects that roughly 5.5 million packages
will be delivered today, or 45 percent of normal volume.
</P>
<P>
UPS officials said the company anticipates more workers will
be called back every day as the package volume stabilizes and
evens out, The United Press International reported from UPS
headquarters in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
Negotiations are scheduled to resume Friday between the company
and a Chicago Teamsters local which is not covered by the national
contract. Local 705, with 11,000 members, is the only local still
on strike, and Local 710 is honoring the picket line. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
