<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Navy Declassifies Cold War-Era Submarine Data </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Navy will declassify
its submarine data from the height of the Cold War and the release
will be a boon to research on climate and the spread of pollution,
a research group said today.
</P>
<P>
The data was gathered by U.S. nuclear submarines on routine
operations in the Arctic Ocean during 1957-1982, the U.S. Arctic
Research Commission said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
It will help geophysicists learn more about the undersea
terrain around the North Pole.
</P>
<P>
The statement added that scientists will be able to use the
data on water depth, latitude, longitude and other particulars to
learn more about how water circulates in the Arctic Ocean, how the
global climate works and possibly how to predict the movement of
contaminants.
</P>
<P>
However, the statement did not say when the submarine data
would be released. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
